WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.990 align:middle line:90%


00:00:00.990 --> 00:00:02.475 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.475 --> 00:00:04.455 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.455 --> 00:00:06.930 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:06.930 --> 00:00:11.403 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.403 --> 00:00:13.070 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Today
we're going to talk

00:00:13.070 --> 00:00:15.680 align:middle line:84%
about the
Szemeredi-Trotter theorem.

00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:17.420 align:middle line:84%
I mentioned the
Szemeredi-Trotter theorem

00:00:17.420 --> 00:00:20.330 align:middle line:84%
on the first day,
and you could think

00:00:20.330 --> 00:00:23.910 align:middle line:84%
of as a fundamental theorem
in projection theory.

00:00:23.910 --> 00:00:29.820 align:middle line:84%
It's one of the rare theorems
that is completely sharp.

00:00:29.820 --> 00:00:31.910 align:middle line:84%
It's just the right answer
for a natural question

00:00:31.910 --> 00:00:32.844 align:middle line:90%
in projection theory.

00:00:32.844 --> 00:00:36.850 align:middle line:90%


00:00:36.850 --> 00:00:37.350 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:00:37.350 --> 00:00:41.360 align:middle line:84%
So we're so we're going
to talk about it and see--

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:43.610 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so there's some
interesting techniques

00:00:43.610 --> 00:00:46.610 align:middle line:90%
involved in it.

00:00:46.610 --> 00:00:47.720 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:00:47.720 --> 00:00:50.570 align:middle line:90%
There, so that's what we'll do.

00:00:50.570 --> 00:00:51.093 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:00:51.093 --> 00:00:52.510 align:middle line:84%
So let me remind
you what it says.

00:00:52.510 --> 00:00:59.140 align:middle line:90%


00:00:59.140 --> 00:01:02.470 align:middle line:84%
So what we talked
about on the first day,

00:01:02.470 --> 00:01:05.200 align:middle line:84%
I called it the
Szemeredi-Trotter projection

00:01:05.200 --> 00:01:05.700 align:middle line:90%
theorem.

00:01:05.700 --> 00:01:08.710 align:middle line:90%


00:01:08.710 --> 00:01:12.880 align:middle line:84%
So the setup was that you
have a finite set in the plane

00:01:12.880 --> 00:01:14.956 align:middle line:84%
and you have a
set of directions.

00:01:14.956 --> 00:01:21.190 align:middle line:90%


00:01:21.190 --> 00:01:27.160 align:middle line:84%
And then S equals S of XD
is the largest projection

00:01:27.160 --> 00:01:29.006 align:middle line:90%
of X in any of these directions.

00:01:29.006 --> 00:01:34.840 align:middle line:90%


00:01:34.840 --> 00:01:37.360 align:middle line:90%
So that's the if.

00:01:37.360 --> 00:01:41.740 align:middle line:84%
And then the conclusion is
that the number of directions

00:01:41.740 --> 00:01:48.280 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by S
squared over X plus 1,

00:01:48.280 --> 00:01:50.560 align:middle line:90%
which we saw in the first.

00:01:50.560 --> 00:01:52.216 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:01:52.216 --> 00:01:54.790 align:middle line:84%
So this theorem is really
a corollary of the theorem

00:01:54.790 --> 00:01:59.190 align:middle line:84%
that they proved that is more
general that I'll state now.

00:01:59.190 --> 00:02:02.100 align:middle line:84%
And the more general
theorem is a theorem

00:02:02.100 --> 00:02:04.715 align:middle line:84%
about how points and lines
intersect in the plane.

00:02:04.715 --> 00:02:13.320 align:middle line:90%


00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:14.535 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:02:14.535 --> 00:02:23.400 align:middle line:84%
So let's say X is a set
of points in the plane

00:02:23.400 --> 00:02:25.700 align:middle line:84%
and L is a set of
lines in the plane.

00:02:25.700 --> 00:02:31.740 align:middle line:90%


00:02:31.740 --> 00:02:39.520 align:middle line:84%
The number of incidences between
X and L is the number of pairs.

00:02:39.520 --> 00:02:42.400 align:middle line:90%
So take a point and a line.

00:02:42.400 --> 00:02:46.710 align:middle line:84%
So that the point
is in the line.

00:02:46.710 --> 00:02:50.100 align:middle line:90%
Let me make a picture.

00:02:50.100 --> 00:02:55.650 align:middle line:84%
So suppose those are our lines
and these are our points.

00:02:55.650 --> 00:02:59.220 align:middle line:90%
How many incidences are there?

00:02:59.220 --> 00:03:02.970 align:middle line:84%
This line has two points
in it, so that counts two.

00:03:02.970 --> 00:03:06.780 align:middle line:84%
And that line has one point
and that line has one point,

00:03:06.780 --> 00:03:08.556 align:middle line:90%
so that's four incidences.

00:03:08.556 --> 00:03:13.230 align:middle line:90%


00:03:13.230 --> 00:03:16.320 align:middle line:84%
You can also think of
this as the sum over all

00:03:16.320 --> 00:03:20.160 align:middle line:84%
the lines in the set of
lines of the number of points

00:03:20.160 --> 00:03:20.825 align:middle line:90%
on that line.

00:03:20.825 --> 00:03:24.810 align:middle line:90%


00:03:24.810 --> 00:03:29.010 align:middle line:84%
This is a way of measuring how
much the points and lines are

00:03:29.010 --> 00:03:32.670 align:middle line:90%
intersecting with each other.

00:03:32.670 --> 00:03:34.860 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:34.860 --> 00:03:41.790 align:middle line:84%
So the general Szemeredi-Trotter
theorem says that if you have

00:03:41.790 --> 00:03:45.630 align:middle line:84%
some points and some lines, the
number of incidences between

00:03:45.630 --> 00:03:50.550 align:middle line:84%
them is bounded by the number of
points plus the number of lines

00:03:50.550 --> 00:03:54.733 align:middle line:84%
plus points to the
2/3 lines to the 2/3.

00:03:54.733 --> 00:04:02.810 align:middle line:90%


00:04:02.810 --> 00:04:03.450 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:03.450 --> 00:04:07.730 align:middle line:84%
Let's look at some examples to
see where this stuff comes from.

00:04:07.730 --> 00:04:09.770 align:middle line:84%
And the examples
will also remind us

00:04:09.770 --> 00:04:11.530 align:middle line:84%
of the connection with
projection theory.

00:04:11.530 --> 00:04:25.740 align:middle line:90%


00:04:25.740 --> 00:04:26.240 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:26.240 --> 00:04:29.420 align:middle line:84%
So how could we
have X incidences?

00:04:29.420 --> 00:04:30.810 align:middle line:90%
That's not too hard to do.

00:04:30.810 --> 00:04:35.660 align:middle line:84%
If you have one line and you
put all the points on it,

00:04:35.660 --> 00:04:37.610 align:middle line:84%
then the number of
incidences is around

00:04:37.610 --> 00:04:41.910 align:middle line:84%
X. How could you
have L incidences?

00:04:41.910 --> 00:04:44.390 align:middle line:84%
That's not too
hard to do either.

00:04:44.390 --> 00:04:47.810 align:middle line:84%
If you have one point and you
have all the lines passing

00:04:47.810 --> 00:04:51.490 align:middle line:84%
through it, then the
number of incidences

00:04:51.490 --> 00:04:52.740 align:middle line:90%
is around the number of lines.

00:04:52.740 --> 00:04:55.630 align:middle line:90%


00:04:55.630 --> 00:04:56.270 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:56.270 --> 00:04:58.840 align:middle line:90%
Now how can you get this?

00:04:58.840 --> 00:05:01.750 align:middle line:84%
This is the most
interesting, and it's

00:05:01.750 --> 00:05:06.850 align:middle line:84%
a fundamentally trickier
example than the first.

00:05:06.850 --> 00:05:09.710 align:middle line:84%
So the third example is
one that we have discussed.

00:05:09.710 --> 00:05:12.280 align:middle line:90%
It's based on an integer grid.

00:05:12.280 --> 00:05:18.375 align:middle line:84%
So let's say X is an
N by N integer grid.

00:05:18.375 --> 00:05:31.240 align:middle line:90%


00:05:31.240 --> 00:05:31.820 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:05:31.820 --> 00:05:35.050 align:middle line:84%
And then we're going to try
to draw some lines that each

00:05:35.050 --> 00:05:36.470 align:middle line:90%
hit many points.

00:05:36.470 --> 00:05:38.860 align:middle line:84%
And we observed in
class on the first day

00:05:38.860 --> 00:05:41.620 align:middle line:84%
that if you have a line
at a rational slope, then

00:05:41.620 --> 00:05:43.370 align:middle line:90%
it will go through many points.

00:05:43.370 --> 00:05:44.475 align:middle line:90%
So those are our lines.

00:05:44.475 --> 00:05:47.443 align:middle line:90%


00:05:47.443 --> 00:05:49.360 align:middle line:84%
So we have to make this
a little more precise.

00:05:49.360 --> 00:05:51.580 align:middle line:84%
So first I'll describe
the rational slopes.

00:05:51.580 --> 00:05:56.010 align:middle line:84%
So Q sub M is defined to
be the fractions a over b

00:05:56.010 --> 00:06:06.090 align:middle line:84%
where a and b are integers, and
the a and b have size at most M.

00:06:06.090 --> 00:06:06.890 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:06:06.890 --> 00:06:13.925 align:middle line:84%
Now our set of lines is the
set of lines with slope in QM.

00:06:13.925 --> 00:06:17.460 align:middle line:90%


00:06:17.460 --> 00:06:26.655 align:middle line:84%
And they pass through
a point of X. OK.

00:06:26.655 --> 00:06:37.200 align:middle line:90%


00:06:37.200 --> 00:06:39.250 align:middle line:84%
This is a good day
for colored chalk.

00:06:39.250 --> 00:06:43.900 align:middle line:84%
So here is a typical line
from our set of lines.

00:06:43.900 --> 00:06:47.930 align:middle line:84%
I pick a rational slope and then
I start at any of the points,

00:06:47.930 --> 00:06:50.230 align:middle line:90%
and I draw a line at that slope.

00:06:50.230 --> 00:06:56.970 align:middle line:90%


00:06:56.970 --> 00:06:57.470 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:06:57.470 --> 00:07:04.610 align:middle line:90%


00:07:04.610 --> 00:07:05.280 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:07:05.280 --> 00:07:09.560 align:middle line:84%
So now let's try to
compute how many points

00:07:09.560 --> 00:07:12.040 align:middle line:84%
and how many lines and how
many incidences this has.

00:07:12.040 --> 00:07:14.780 align:middle line:90%


00:07:14.780 --> 00:07:15.660 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:07:15.660 --> 00:07:19.110 align:middle line:90%
So the size of X is N squared.

00:07:19.110 --> 00:07:20.390 align:middle line:90%
It's easy to see.

00:07:20.390 --> 00:07:23.300 align:middle line:84%
How many different slopes
are we talking about?

00:07:23.300 --> 00:07:26.760 align:middle line:84%
Well, the number of fractions
is around M squared.

00:07:26.760 --> 00:07:29.240 align:middle line:90%
Some of those are reducible.

00:07:29.240 --> 00:07:32.060 align:middle line:84%
But it turns out that the
number of distinct fractions

00:07:32.060 --> 00:07:35.510 align:middle line:90%
is still around M squared.

00:07:35.510 --> 00:07:44.290 align:middle line:84%
So this is not trivial
but not difficult.

00:07:44.290 --> 00:07:46.040 align:middle line:84%
Maybe I'll put a little
something about it

00:07:46.040 --> 00:07:46.707 align:middle line:90%
on the homework.

00:07:46.707 --> 00:07:50.880 align:middle line:90%


00:07:50.880 --> 00:07:55.710 align:middle line:84%
So now, how many
incidences do we have?

00:07:55.710 --> 00:08:00.050 align:middle line:84%
And we can say that,
well, each point

00:08:00.050 --> 00:08:03.030 align:middle line:84%
is in a line of every
one of these slopes.

00:08:03.030 --> 00:08:04.760 align:middle line:84%
So the number of
incidences is the number

00:08:04.760 --> 00:08:07.020 align:middle line:84%
of points times
number of slopes.

00:08:07.020 --> 00:08:09.565 align:middle line:84%
So that's N squared
times M squared.

00:08:09.565 --> 00:08:13.130 align:middle line:90%


00:08:13.130 --> 00:08:13.930 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:08:13.930 --> 00:08:20.690 align:middle line:84%
Now how many different
lines do we have?

00:08:20.690 --> 00:08:22.713 align:middle line:84%
Well, we have M
squared directions,

00:08:22.713 --> 00:08:24.380 align:middle line:84%
so we have to think
about how many lines

00:08:24.380 --> 00:08:25.347 align:middle line:90%
are in each direction.

00:08:25.347 --> 00:08:26.930 align:middle line:84%
And actually thinking
about the number

00:08:26.930 --> 00:08:28.820 align:middle line:84%
of lines in each
direction, really you

00:08:28.820 --> 00:08:31.700 align:middle line:84%
can think of it in terms
of projection theory.

00:08:31.700 --> 00:08:35.720 align:middle line:84%
So suppose S is one
of our directions.

00:08:35.720 --> 00:08:38.750 align:middle line:84%
Let's say pi sub
S, the projection

00:08:38.750 --> 00:08:46.510 align:middle line:84%
at slope S of X1 and X2
is X2 minus SX1, I guess.

00:08:46.510 --> 00:09:02.170 align:middle line:84%
The projection whose fibers
are lines of slope S.

00:09:02.170 --> 00:09:03.280 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:09:03.280 --> 00:09:10.270 align:middle line:84%
And so the number of
lines in direction S

00:09:10.270 --> 00:09:14.666 align:middle line:84%
is exactly the size
of this projection.

00:09:14.666 --> 00:09:20.710 align:middle line:90%


00:09:20.710 --> 00:09:21.550 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:09:21.550 --> 00:09:23.450 align:middle line:90%
And how big is the projection?

00:09:23.450 --> 00:09:26.530 align:middle line:84%
Well, so let's make
a little lemma.

00:09:26.530 --> 00:09:31.940 align:middle line:90%
So S is in QM and X is as above.

00:09:31.940 --> 00:09:38.110 align:middle line:84%
Then the size of this projection
is bounded by M times N.

00:09:38.110 --> 00:09:41.970 align:middle line:90%
So, proof.

00:09:41.970 --> 00:09:42.520 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:09:42.520 --> 00:09:48.480 align:middle line:84%
So we have X1 and X2 are
integers between 1 and N,

00:09:48.480 --> 00:09:52.740 align:middle line:90%
and S is a over b.

00:09:52.740 --> 00:09:58.170 align:middle line:84%
So if I take pi S of the
point X1, X2, I have--

00:09:58.170 --> 00:09:58.680 align:middle line:90%
what is it?

00:09:58.680 --> 00:10:06.450 align:middle line:84%
X2 minus a over b X1, which I'll
put over a common denominator.

00:10:06.450 --> 00:10:12.900 align:middle line:90%
So it's b X2 minus a X1 over b.

00:10:12.900 --> 00:10:18.780 align:middle line:84%
And this here is an integer
of size at most, like,

00:10:18.780 --> 00:10:22.120 align:middle line:90%
M times N. M times n.

00:10:22.120 --> 00:10:24.810 align:middle line:90%


00:10:24.810 --> 00:10:26.970 align:middle line:84%
So there are at most
M times N choices

00:10:26.970 --> 00:10:29.825 align:middle line:84%
for what this could
be up to a constant.

00:10:29.825 --> 00:10:35.970 align:middle line:90%


00:10:35.970 --> 00:10:36.520 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:10:36.520 --> 00:10:39.530 align:middle line:84%
So therefore, the
number of lines

00:10:39.530 --> 00:10:44.720 align:middle line:84%
is smaller than the
number of slopes

00:10:44.720 --> 00:10:49.190 align:middle line:90%
times M times N lines per slope.

00:10:49.190 --> 00:10:57.950 align:middle line:90%
So that's like M cubed N.

00:10:57.950 --> 00:10:59.582 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:10:59.582 --> 00:11:01.740 align:middle line:84%
These are written
as upper bounds.

00:11:01.740 --> 00:11:04.700 align:middle line:84%
There are also
matching lower bounds,

00:11:04.700 --> 00:11:08.720 align:middle line:84%
so those upper bounds
are actually tight.

00:11:08.720 --> 00:11:13.010 align:middle line:84%
And if you do a little algebra,
you will see that the incidence

00:11:13.010 --> 00:11:21.161 align:middle line:84%
is between X and L. So at least
L to the 2/3, X to the 2/3.

00:11:21.161 --> 00:11:25.220 align:middle line:84%
Just by plugging in
that this is L, that's

00:11:25.220 --> 00:11:30.937 align:middle line:84%
the number of incidences,
and that's X. So

00:11:30.937 --> 00:11:32.395 align:middle line:84%
that's where this
thing comes from.

00:11:32.395 --> 00:11:45.449 align:middle line:90%


00:11:45.449 --> 00:11:45.949 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:11:45.949 --> 00:11:49.621 align:middle line:90%


00:11:49.621 --> 00:11:51.490 align:middle line:84%
So the two main
ingredients, we're

00:11:51.490 --> 00:11:53.350 align:middle line:84%
checking how many
directions there that

00:11:53.350 --> 00:11:56.290 align:middle line:84%
have slope-- how many
rational numbers are there

00:11:56.290 --> 00:12:01.430 align:middle line:84%
with height up to M and how big
is each of these projections.

00:12:01.430 --> 00:12:03.310 align:middle line:84%
And you can take those
same computations

00:12:03.310 --> 00:12:06.630 align:middle line:84%
and feed it into the
projection theory setup here.

00:12:06.630 --> 00:12:09.400 align:middle line:90%


00:12:09.400 --> 00:12:12.340 align:middle line:90%
You would get theorem one.

00:12:12.340 --> 00:12:14.925 align:middle line:84%
You would get that this is a
sharp example for theorem one.

00:12:14.925 --> 00:12:22.960 align:middle line:90%


00:12:22.960 --> 00:12:25.663 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:12:25.663 --> 00:12:27.330 align:middle line:84%
I will pause for
questions and comments.

00:12:27.330 --> 00:12:38.110 align:middle line:90%


00:12:38.110 --> 00:12:39.110 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:12:39.110 --> 00:12:41.890 align:middle line:84%
So this example,
you can see from it

00:12:41.890 --> 00:12:44.930 align:middle line:84%
that theorem one and theorem
two are related to each other.

00:12:44.930 --> 00:12:47.350 align:middle line:84%
And theorem two is more
general because this

00:12:47.350 --> 00:12:49.130 align:middle line:90%
could be any set of lines.

00:12:49.130 --> 00:12:52.750 align:middle line:84%
Whereas in theorem one, in
the projection theory setup,

00:12:52.750 --> 00:12:54.670 align:middle line:84%
we would have a
set of directions D

00:12:54.670 --> 00:12:57.520 align:middle line:84%
and the set of lines would be
all the lines in direction D

00:12:57.520 --> 00:12:59.860 align:middle line:84%
that go through a
point of X. So that's

00:12:59.860 --> 00:13:02.030 align:middle line:84%
a somewhat specific
set of lines,

00:13:02.030 --> 00:13:03.240 align:middle line:90%
and this one is more general.

00:13:03.240 --> 00:13:06.010 align:middle line:90%


00:13:06.010 --> 00:13:07.666 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:13:07.666 --> 00:13:10.550 align:middle line:84%
So it's not very difficult
to get from here to here,

00:13:10.550 --> 00:13:11.857 align:middle line:90%
and it's not that interesting.

00:13:11.857 --> 00:13:14.190 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to leave it as
an exercise on the homework.

00:13:14.190 --> 00:13:21.100 align:middle line:90%


00:13:21.100 --> 00:13:21.960 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:13:21.960 --> 00:13:24.520 align:middle line:84%
Now another question that
came up on the first day

00:13:24.520 --> 00:13:28.540 align:middle line:84%
is, are there other examples
in projection theory

00:13:28.540 --> 00:13:33.510 align:middle line:84%
besides this square grid
that also are that also are

00:13:33.510 --> 00:13:35.130 align:middle line:90%
sharp for Szemeredi-Trotter?

00:13:35.130 --> 00:13:36.940 align:middle line:84%
And there are very
few that are known.

00:13:36.940 --> 00:13:40.270 align:middle line:84%
But since we just did
this, I can tell you a bit

00:13:40.270 --> 00:13:44.490 align:middle line:84%
the other ones, and
it's conceivable

00:13:44.490 --> 00:13:47.200 align:middle line:84%
that the list I'll
show you is everything.

00:13:47.200 --> 00:14:00.510 align:middle line:90%


00:14:00.510 --> 00:14:02.430 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:02.430 --> 00:14:08.226 align:middle line:84%
So what are the sharp examples
for Szemeredi-Trotter?

00:14:08.226 --> 00:14:14.030 align:middle line:90%


00:14:14.030 --> 00:14:14.530 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:14.530 --> 00:14:18.070 align:middle line:84%
So we've just seen the
historically first example,

00:14:18.070 --> 00:14:21.515 align:middle line:90%
which is a square integer grid.

00:14:21.515 --> 00:14:24.510 align:middle line:90%


00:14:24.510 --> 00:14:29.190 align:middle line:84%
And that goes back to
Erdos in the '60s, I think.

00:14:29.190 --> 00:14:32.240 align:middle line:84%
There's a second example, which
is a rather small variation

00:14:32.240 --> 00:14:33.860 align:middle line:84%
on it, but we know
so few examples

00:14:33.860 --> 00:14:35.310 align:middle line:90%
that it's worth mentioning.

00:14:35.310 --> 00:14:38.370 align:middle line:84%
It is a rectangular
integer grid.

00:14:38.370 --> 00:14:43.610 align:middle line:90%


00:14:43.610 --> 00:14:47.270 align:middle line:90%
And that was done by allocation.

00:14:47.270 --> 00:14:51.350 align:middle line:84%
So instead of N by
N, just put N1 by N2

00:14:51.350 --> 00:14:55.220 align:middle line:90%
and then do a similar analysis.

00:14:55.220 --> 00:14:57.470 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:57.470 --> 00:14:59.970 align:middle line:84%
Then there is a third
thing that we can do,

00:14:59.970 --> 00:15:07.190 align:middle line:84%
which is to replace the integers
by integers in some other number

00:15:07.190 --> 00:15:07.800 align:middle line:90%
field.

00:15:07.800 --> 00:15:12.470 align:middle line:84%
So for example, integers
adjoin the square root

00:15:12.470 --> 00:15:18.213 align:middle line:90%
of 2, or perhaps other numbers.

00:15:18.213 --> 00:15:24.410 align:middle line:90%


00:15:24.410 --> 00:15:25.234 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:15:25.234 --> 00:15:30.408 align:middle line:84%
So this is in a paper by
Olivine Silier and myself,

00:15:30.408 --> 00:15:32.200 align:middle line:84%
and it's actually only
currently worked out

00:15:32.200 --> 00:15:34.180 align:middle line:84%
for some special number
fields, but I suspect

00:15:34.180 --> 00:15:35.900 align:middle line:90%
it works for any number field.

00:15:35.900 --> 00:15:38.482 align:middle line:84%
If anybody knows more about
number fields than me,

00:15:38.482 --> 00:15:39.940 align:middle line:84%
this could be a
nice little project

00:15:39.940 --> 00:15:41.240 align:middle line:90%
to work it out correctly.

00:15:41.240 --> 00:15:41.950 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:15:41.950 --> 00:15:44.410 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: One question
about the rectangular grid.

00:15:44.410 --> 00:15:47.690 align:middle line:84%
Is there any restriction on
the aspect ratio of the grid,

00:15:47.690 --> 00:15:51.190 align:middle line:90%
like a ratio of 1 to 2?

00:15:51.190 --> 00:15:52.875 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah,
there probably is.

00:15:52.875 --> 00:15:56.260 align:middle line:90%


00:15:56.260 --> 00:15:56.840 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:15:56.840 --> 00:15:59.150 align:middle line:84%
So it takes a little
writing and whatever.

00:15:59.150 --> 00:16:03.020 align:middle line:84%
You see what happens for
each one, each N1 and N2.

00:16:03.020 --> 00:16:03.520 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:16:03.520 --> 00:16:06.370 align:middle line:84%
But there are sharp
examples that involve

00:16:06.370 --> 00:16:07.650 align:middle line:90%
grids that are not square.

00:16:07.650 --> 00:16:11.945 align:middle line:90%


00:16:11.945 --> 00:16:12.445 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:16:12.445 --> 00:16:16.600 align:middle line:84%
So let me say a little more
precisely what this means here.

00:16:16.600 --> 00:16:21.730 align:middle line:84%
So we would have a set in
our ring of things of height

00:16:21.730 --> 00:16:22.760 align:middle line:90%
up to N.

00:16:22.760 --> 00:16:27.090 align:middle line:84%
So that would be the set
a1 plus square root of 2,

00:16:27.090 --> 00:16:34.170 align:middle line:84%
a2 and with the property with--
so with a1 and a2 integers

00:16:34.170 --> 00:16:41.143 align:middle line:84%
and of size up to
N. And our new QM.

00:16:41.143 --> 00:16:44.940 align:middle line:90%


00:16:44.940 --> 00:16:46.180 align:middle line:90%
Maybe QRM.

00:16:46.180 --> 00:16:48.540 align:middle line:84%
So quotients in
this ring size M.

00:16:48.540 --> 00:16:53.130 align:middle line:84%
This would be quotients of
the form a1 plus root 2 a2

00:16:53.130 --> 00:17:01.230 align:middle line:84%
over b1 plus root 2 b2, where
the ai and bi are integers

00:17:01.230 --> 00:17:07.480 align:middle line:90%
and they have norm to M.

00:17:07.480 --> 00:17:07.980 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:17:07.980 --> 00:17:10.030 align:middle line:84%
And now we can do
the same thing.

00:17:10.030 --> 00:17:19.569 align:middle line:84%
So L is the set of
lines with slope in QRM,

00:17:19.569 --> 00:17:27.490 align:middle line:84%
and they go through a
point of X. Oh, sorry.

00:17:27.490 --> 00:17:29.190 align:middle line:90%
So X is just RN by RN.

00:17:29.190 --> 00:17:34.860 align:middle line:90%


00:17:34.860 --> 00:17:36.148 align:middle line:90%
So that's the example.

00:17:36.148 --> 00:17:37.690 align:middle line:84%
And then if you
compute a little bit,

00:17:37.690 --> 00:17:39.648 align:middle line:84%
you'll see that everything
goes in a way that's

00:17:39.648 --> 00:17:42.930 align:middle line:90%
analogous to the first example.

00:17:42.930 --> 00:17:47.680 align:middle line:84%
And I guess I erased the key
points, which was unwise.

00:17:47.680 --> 00:17:51.150 align:middle line:84%
But if you think through
the first example,

00:17:51.150 --> 00:17:52.900 align:middle line:90%
we used an integer grid.

00:17:52.900 --> 00:17:54.820 align:middle line:90%
What did we use about integers?

00:17:54.820 --> 00:17:57.540 align:middle line:84%
Basically we just
used that integers

00:17:57.540 --> 00:18:00.960 align:middle line:84%
are closed under taking
products and taking sums.

00:18:00.960 --> 00:18:02.500 align:middle line:84%
That was what we
used in our proof.

00:18:02.500 --> 00:18:05.680 align:middle line:84%
And this is a ring,
this is a ring,

00:18:05.680 --> 00:18:08.880 align:middle line:84%
so these guys are also, in a
similar way, closed under taking

00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:10.210 align:middle line:90%
products and taking sums.

00:18:10.210 --> 00:18:11.470 align:middle line:90%
So it works the same way.

00:18:11.470 --> 00:18:14.560 align:middle line:90%


00:18:14.560 --> 00:18:15.060 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:18:15.060 --> 00:18:20.130 align:middle line:90%


00:18:20.130 --> 00:18:21.010 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:18:21.010 --> 00:18:24.860 align:middle line:84%
So it's a big mystery
in the field to have

00:18:24.860 --> 00:18:27.350 align:middle line:84%
what's called an inverse
theorem for Szemeredi-Trotter.

00:18:27.350 --> 00:18:33.770 align:middle line:84%
An inverse theorem would say
that if you had a set X and L

00:18:33.770 --> 00:18:37.670 align:middle line:84%
where this was tight and
especially where this dominated,

00:18:37.670 --> 00:18:40.580 align:middle line:84%
then what could you
say about X and L?

00:18:40.580 --> 00:18:44.360 align:middle line:84%
Or as a special case,
if you had a set

00:18:44.360 --> 00:18:47.360 align:middle line:84%
X and a set of directions
D where this is tight,

00:18:47.360 --> 00:18:49.090 align:middle line:84%
what could you
say about X and D?

00:18:49.090 --> 00:18:51.770 align:middle line:90%


00:18:51.770 --> 00:18:53.327 align:middle line:84%
On the one hand,
we have a handful

00:18:53.327 --> 00:18:55.160 align:middle line:84%
of examples where they're
tight, and they're

00:18:55.160 --> 00:18:57.180 align:middle line:84%
based on a lot of
algebraic structure.

00:18:57.180 --> 00:19:00.950 align:middle line:84%
They're based on the ring of
integers in some number field.

00:19:00.950 --> 00:19:03.620 align:middle line:84%
And on the other hand,
we have very little

00:19:03.620 --> 00:19:04.740 align:middle line:90%
in the way of theorems.

00:19:04.740 --> 00:19:09.590 align:middle line:84%
That's about what we can
definitely say about X and L

00:19:09.590 --> 00:19:10.480 align:middle line:90%
if this is tight.

00:19:10.480 --> 00:19:15.560 align:middle line:90%


00:19:15.560 --> 00:19:17.280 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:19:17.280 --> 00:19:20.460 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: From [INAUDIBLE]
quadratic number field examples,

00:19:20.460 --> 00:19:23.950 align:middle line:84%
is it important for it to be
a unique factorization domain?

00:19:23.950 --> 00:19:26.270 align:middle line:84%
Because it seems
like if that fails,

00:19:26.270 --> 00:19:29.818 align:middle line:84%
then you get kind of extra
collapsing along objections.

00:19:29.818 --> 00:19:31.360 align:middle line:84%
But I don't know if
that's a problem.

00:19:31.360 --> 00:19:32.193 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:19:32.193 --> 00:19:33.970 align:middle line:84%
So the question
is, is it important

00:19:33.970 --> 00:19:40.000 align:middle line:84%
whether our ring has
unique factorization?

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:42.640 align:middle line:84%
I don't think it's
too important.

00:19:42.640 --> 00:19:44.440 align:middle line:84%
In our proof over
the integers, I

00:19:44.440 --> 00:19:46.773 align:middle line:84%
don't think we used unique
factorization of integers.

00:19:46.773 --> 00:19:50.440 align:middle line:90%


00:19:50.440 --> 00:19:52.300 align:middle line:84%
But there are some
things we would

00:19:52.300 --> 00:19:54.350 align:middle line:84%
have to check about
each number field.

00:19:54.350 --> 00:19:58.480 align:middle line:84%
Like, we'd have to check that
how many quotients are there

00:19:58.480 --> 00:19:59.886 align:middle line:90%
in this thing of quotients.

00:19:59.886 --> 00:20:03.130 align:middle line:90%


00:20:03.130 --> 00:20:03.890 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:20:03.890 --> 00:20:07.120 align:middle line:84%
So anyway, so I'll
put something about it

00:20:07.120 --> 00:20:09.310 align:middle line:84%
on the problem set as an
optional project for people

00:20:09.310 --> 00:20:11.660 align:middle line:90%
who want to explore.

00:20:11.660 --> 00:20:12.160 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:20:12.160 --> 00:20:16.186 align:middle line:90%


00:20:16.186 --> 00:20:18.440 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: For the original
integer grid case,

00:20:18.440 --> 00:20:22.050 align:middle line:84%
we required lines that
have different slopes.

00:20:22.050 --> 00:20:24.990 align:middle line:84%
Here, do we have
some requirements

00:20:24.990 --> 00:20:27.093 align:middle line:90%
on our choice of ai, bi?

00:20:27.093 --> 00:20:30.490 align:middle line:90%


00:20:30.490 --> 00:20:31.240 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: OK.

00:20:31.240 --> 00:20:34.900 align:middle line:84%
So I think the comment is
that in the original case.

00:20:34.900 --> 00:20:37.535 align:middle line:84%
I said that the a over b
should be a reduced fraction.

00:20:37.535 --> 00:20:38.160 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:20:38.160 --> 00:20:39.870 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: And do we
have an analog of that?

00:20:39.870 --> 00:20:40.495 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:20:40.495 --> 00:20:42.240 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:20:42.240 --> 00:20:43.280 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, we do.

00:20:43.280 --> 00:20:46.080 align:middle line:90%


00:20:46.080 --> 00:20:46.690 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:20:46.690 --> 00:20:49.630 align:middle line:84%
So this is the set of all
the fractions a over b.

00:20:49.630 --> 00:20:53.202 align:middle line:84%
And if a given real number--
if a given rational number

00:20:53.202 --> 00:20:54.910 align:middle line:84%
can be represented in
two different ways,

00:20:54.910 --> 00:20:57.250 align:middle line:90%
it still only counts once in QM.

00:20:57.250 --> 00:20:59.580 align:middle line:90%
And the same thing is true here.

00:20:59.580 --> 00:21:02.670 align:middle line:84%
So the same number
here might have

00:21:02.670 --> 00:21:05.400 align:middle line:84%
more than one representation
of this flavor, which

00:21:05.400 --> 00:21:10.020 align:middle line:84%
makes it not trivial to count
the cardinality of this set.

00:21:10.020 --> 00:21:12.660 align:middle line:84%
And we do need to know the
cardinality of this set

00:21:12.660 --> 00:21:14.210 align:middle line:90%
to correctly analyze things.

00:21:14.210 --> 00:21:20.438 align:middle line:90%


00:21:20.438 --> 00:21:22.230 align:middle line:84%
I guess something like
unique factorization

00:21:22.230 --> 00:21:23.465 align:middle line:90%
could come in there.

00:21:23.465 --> 00:21:26.016 align:middle line:90%


00:21:26.016 --> 00:21:29.468 align:middle line:84%
Before, I said put it in lowest
terms, which is maybe not

00:21:29.468 --> 00:21:31.260 align:middle line:84%
quite as clear what
that means if you don't

00:21:31.260 --> 00:21:33.840 align:middle line:90%
have unique factorization.

00:21:33.840 --> 00:21:35.160 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:21:35.160 --> 00:21:39.380 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So say in the regime,
X is greater than L squared.

00:21:39.380 --> 00:21:42.750 align:middle line:90%


00:21:42.750 --> 00:21:46.270 align:middle line:84%
Can you see that L squared
dominates in some way

00:21:46.270 --> 00:21:51.900 align:middle line:84%
and there's no other examples
like the square root quotient?

00:21:51.900 --> 00:21:52.800 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:21:52.800 --> 00:21:54.510 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:21:54.510 --> 00:21:56.340 align:middle line:84%
Let me say the question
back and then I'll

00:21:56.340 --> 00:21:57.670 align:middle line:90%
make sure I understand.

00:21:57.670 --> 00:21:58.462 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:21:58.462 --> 00:22:00.750 align:middle line:84%
So if you look at
this right-hand side,

00:22:00.750 --> 00:22:03.120 align:middle line:84%
different terms will
dominate depending

00:22:03.120 --> 00:22:05.260 align:middle line:84%
upon the relative
sizes of X and L.

00:22:05.260 --> 00:22:06.763 align:middle line:90%
And there's different regimes.

00:22:06.763 --> 00:22:11.430 align:middle line:90%


00:22:11.430 --> 00:22:17.180 align:middle line:84%
So one regime is that X could
be bigger than L squared.

00:22:17.180 --> 00:22:21.000 align:middle line:84%
So you have just a ton of
points and not very many lines.

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:24.080 align:middle line:84%
And in that situation,
this term is bigger

00:22:24.080 --> 00:22:25.950 align:middle line:90%
than that term and that term.

00:22:25.950 --> 00:22:28.680 align:middle line:84%
So in this situation,
the X dominates.

00:22:28.680 --> 00:22:33.080 align:middle line:90%


00:22:33.080 --> 00:22:37.790 align:middle line:84%
So I think the question was,
can we describe some structure

00:22:37.790 --> 00:22:39.530 align:middle line:90%
theorem in this case?

00:22:39.530 --> 00:22:40.070 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:22:40.070 --> 00:22:41.490 align:middle line:90%
So I think we can.

00:22:41.490 --> 00:22:47.330 align:middle line:84%
So in that case, the
example is example one here.

00:22:47.330 --> 00:22:49.550 align:middle line:84%
And so the structure
theorem would say

00:22:49.550 --> 00:22:53.780 align:middle line:90%
that you really have to have--

00:22:53.780 --> 00:23:00.263 align:middle line:90%
well, there may not--

00:23:00.263 --> 00:23:00.930 align:middle line:90%
let me say that.

00:23:00.930 --> 00:23:03.990 align:middle line:84%
So in this regime, I don't think
there's that much structure.

00:23:03.990 --> 00:23:06.810 align:middle line:84%
So I have some
lines, not very many.

00:23:06.810 --> 00:23:11.160 align:middle line:84%
And then I have a ton of points
and I want to have x incidences.

00:23:11.160 --> 00:23:14.850 align:middle line:84%
That means I had better put
each of my points on a line.

00:23:14.850 --> 00:23:18.320 align:middle line:84%
So I put each point
wherever I like,

00:23:18.320 --> 00:23:21.000 align:middle line:84%
not off in the middle of space,
but on one of these lines.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:23.600 align:middle line:84%
And then I get this
many incidences.

00:23:23.600 --> 00:23:25.370 align:middle line:84%
So there's not that
much of a structure

00:23:25.370 --> 00:23:27.890 align:middle line:90%
theorem we could ask for here.

00:23:27.890 --> 00:23:30.210 align:middle line:84%
And there's not that much
of a structure theory

00:23:30.210 --> 00:23:32.250 align:middle line:84%
we could ask for
when this dominates.

00:23:32.250 --> 00:23:36.330 align:middle line:84%
But here, if that one dominates,
there are very few examples

00:23:36.330 --> 00:23:39.290 align:middle line:84%
and there could be
a structure theory.

00:23:39.290 --> 00:23:40.310 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:23:40.310 --> 00:23:43.430 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Sharp
example in theorem two

00:23:43.430 --> 00:23:47.630 align:middle line:84%
has to be sharp example
in the projection

00:23:47.630 --> 00:23:49.797 align:middle line:90%
version of the theorem?

00:23:49.797 --> 00:23:50.630 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:23:50.630 --> 00:23:53.630 align:middle line:84%
So the question is, how do
sharp examples in the two things

00:23:53.630 --> 00:23:55.070 align:middle line:90%
compare?

00:23:55.070 --> 00:23:57.890 align:middle line:84%
So if you start with a sharp
example in the projection

00:23:57.890 --> 00:24:02.070 align:middle line:84%
theorem, then you can
make a set of lines.

00:24:02.070 --> 00:24:03.860 align:middle line:84%
That's the set of
lines that go through X

00:24:03.860 --> 00:24:09.040 align:middle line:84%
and have directions in D. And
that will become a sharp example

00:24:09.040 --> 00:24:11.623 align:middle line:90%
in the general theorem.

00:24:11.623 --> 00:24:14.290 align:middle line:84%
Now, if you start with the sharp
example in the general theorem,

00:24:14.290 --> 00:24:16.020 align:middle line:84%
it may not have the
special form that

00:24:16.020 --> 00:24:18.220 align:middle line:84%
makes it relevant for
the projection theorem,

00:24:18.220 --> 00:24:20.905 align:middle line:90%
so you can't go the other way.

00:24:20.905 --> 00:24:25.365 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So you
always have to do that.

00:24:25.365 --> 00:24:30.210 align:middle line:84%
The sharp example, they
are like the rectangle

00:24:30.210 --> 00:24:35.620 align:middle line:84%
with the square grid and
the later one, all of them,

00:24:35.620 --> 00:24:39.960 align:middle line:90%
they are sharp for both cases.

00:24:39.960 --> 00:24:40.800 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:24:40.800 --> 00:24:43.110 align:middle line:84%
So all the sharp
examples we mentioned

00:24:43.110 --> 00:24:45.440 align:middle line:84%
are sharp examples
for both cases.

00:24:45.440 --> 00:24:48.270 align:middle line:90%


00:24:48.270 --> 00:24:49.270 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:24:49.270 --> 00:24:51.510 align:middle line:84%
I guess there's one
more comment about it,

00:24:51.510 --> 00:24:55.920 align:middle line:84%
that this setup
is invariant under

00:24:55.920 --> 00:24:57.910 align:middle line:90%
projective transformations.

00:24:57.910 --> 00:25:01.020 align:middle line:84%
Projective transformations take
lines to lines and of course

00:25:01.020 --> 00:25:02.440 align:middle line:90%
take points to points.

00:25:02.440 --> 00:25:05.110 align:middle line:84%
And so if you start
with a sharp example,

00:25:05.110 --> 00:25:07.170 align:middle line:84%
maybe coming from
a grid, you can

00:25:07.170 --> 00:25:09.210 align:middle line:84%
apply a projective
transformation to it

00:25:09.210 --> 00:25:12.590 align:middle line:84%
and get a new sharp
example for this theorem.

00:25:12.590 --> 00:25:14.720 align:middle line:84%
But it won't any
longer correspond

00:25:14.720 --> 00:25:15.960 align:middle line:90%
to the projection set.

00:25:15.960 --> 00:25:18.620 align:middle line:90%


00:25:18.620 --> 00:25:20.552 align:middle line:84%
OK, so the full list
of sharp examples

00:25:20.552 --> 00:25:22.010 align:middle line:84%
for this theorem
that we know about

00:25:22.010 --> 00:25:24.180 align:middle line:84%
is the ones I just
wrote on the board, plus

00:25:24.180 --> 00:25:26.310 align:middle line:84%
you can apply projective
transformations.

00:25:26.310 --> 00:25:29.950 align:middle line:90%


00:25:29.950 --> 00:25:30.450 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:25:30.450 --> 00:25:32.325 align:middle line:84%
In terms of proving an
inverse theorem, which

00:25:32.325 --> 00:25:35.570 align:middle line:84%
is a big open problem, proving
an inverse theorem for this

00:25:35.570 --> 00:25:39.170 align:middle line:84%
would be harder and more general
than proving an inverse theorem

00:25:39.170 --> 00:25:40.216 align:middle line:90%
for the projections.

00:25:40.216 --> 00:25:43.250 align:middle line:90%


00:25:43.250 --> 00:25:45.300 align:middle line:84%
The one for projections,
we don't know either,

00:25:45.300 --> 00:25:46.967 align:middle line:84%
and that would be a
good starting point.

00:25:46.967 --> 00:25:48.510 align:middle line:84%
It might be a little
more accessible.

00:25:48.510 --> 00:25:56.510 align:middle line:90%


00:25:56.510 --> 00:25:57.080 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:25:57.080 --> 00:25:59.360 align:middle line:90%
Let's keep going.

00:25:59.360 --> 00:26:02.660 align:middle line:84%
So the goal for the
class is to describe how

00:26:02.660 --> 00:26:06.640 align:middle line:90%
to prove this theorem right.

00:26:06.640 --> 00:26:09.140 align:middle line:84%
The first estimate I'd like to
show you is a double counting

00:26:09.140 --> 00:26:11.405 align:middle line:84%
estimate for the
incidences, which

00:26:11.405 --> 00:26:13.280 align:middle line:84%
is in a similar flavor
to the double counting

00:26:13.280 --> 00:26:15.150 align:middle line:84%
estimates we've done
earlier in the class.

00:26:15.150 --> 00:26:17.668 align:middle line:84%
But let's just see how much
double counting tells us

00:26:17.668 --> 00:26:18.460 align:middle line:90%
about this problem.

00:26:18.460 --> 00:26:43.190 align:middle line:90%


00:26:43.190 --> 00:26:43.870 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:26:43.870 --> 00:26:46.460 align:middle line:90%


00:26:46.460 --> 00:26:48.235 align:middle line:90%
So double counting.

00:26:48.235 --> 00:26:53.810 align:middle line:90%


00:26:53.810 --> 00:26:54.360 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:26:54.360 --> 00:26:57.990 align:middle line:84%
So by double counting we will
prove the following estimate.

00:26:57.990 --> 00:26:59.390 align:middle line:90%
I'll call it lemma one.

00:26:59.390 --> 00:27:04.700 align:middle line:84%
The incidence is between X
and L are bounded by X times L

00:27:04.700 --> 00:27:11.440 align:middle line:90%
to the 1/2 plus L. All right.

00:27:11.440 --> 00:27:14.435 align:middle line:90%
So here's the proof.

00:27:14.435 --> 00:27:14.935 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:27:14.935 --> 00:27:20.390 align:middle line:84%
So the incidences are
the sum over the lines,

00:27:20.390 --> 00:27:24.610 align:middle line:84%
and I count how many
points are on each line.

00:27:24.610 --> 00:27:27.250 align:middle line:84%
And now I'm going to
Cauchy-Schwarz that.

00:27:27.250 --> 00:27:37.690 align:middle line:90%
So it's less than that.

00:27:37.690 --> 00:27:46.750 align:middle line:90%


00:27:46.750 --> 00:27:47.450 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:27:47.450 --> 00:27:50.530 align:middle line:84%
So what do I gain by
Cauchy-Schwarzing it?

00:27:50.530 --> 00:27:58.390 align:middle line:84%
Well, if you think about
the number of points

00:27:58.390 --> 00:28:04.410 align:middle line:84%
on this line squared, it's very
similar to counting the number

00:28:04.410 --> 00:28:09.300 align:middle line:90%
of pairs of points on the line.

00:28:09.300 --> 00:28:11.310 align:middle line:84%
And then we can
make use of the fact

00:28:11.310 --> 00:28:16.350 align:middle line:84%
that for any pair of points,
it only lies on one line.

00:28:16.350 --> 00:28:17.260 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:28:17.260 --> 00:28:23.970 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to
bound this by here.

00:28:23.970 --> 00:28:27.220 align:middle line:90%
OK, so it's not quite true.

00:28:27.220 --> 00:28:28.720 align:middle line:84%
Let me say something
in parentheses.

00:28:28.720 --> 00:28:31.530 align:middle line:84%
It is not quite
true that the number

00:28:31.530 --> 00:28:34.440 align:middle line:84%
of points on the line
squared is smaller

00:28:34.440 --> 00:28:40.920 align:middle line:84%
than the number of points
on the line choose two.

00:28:40.920 --> 00:28:43.170 align:middle line:84%
That would be true if the
number of points on the line

00:28:43.170 --> 00:28:43.930 align:middle line:90%
is pretty large.

00:28:43.930 --> 00:28:46.305 align:middle line:84%
But if there's only one point
on the line, then this is 1

00:28:46.305 --> 00:28:47.370 align:middle line:90%
and this is 0.

00:28:47.370 --> 00:28:50.190 align:middle line:90%
So I have to add here.

00:28:50.190 --> 00:28:51.395 align:middle line:90%
I guess I can just add one.

00:28:51.395 --> 00:28:56.160 align:middle line:90%


00:28:56.160 --> 00:28:56.800 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:28:56.800 --> 00:28:59.110 align:middle line:90%
So now I get two terms.

00:28:59.110 --> 00:29:07.110 align:middle line:84%
So this one contributes
number of points on the line

00:29:07.110 --> 00:29:07.975 align:middle line:90%
choose two.

00:29:07.975 --> 00:29:11.540 align:middle line:90%


00:29:11.540 --> 00:29:15.200 align:middle line:84%
All I'm doing is
changing this to this,

00:29:15.200 --> 00:29:18.980 align:middle line:84%
and then I still
have my L to the 1/2.

00:29:18.980 --> 00:29:23.330 align:middle line:84%
And then if I put in one
here, this gives me the number

00:29:23.330 --> 00:29:26.510 align:middle line:84%
of lines to the 1/2 which groups
with that and I get the number

00:29:26.510 --> 00:29:27.670 align:middle line:90%
of lines.

00:29:27.670 --> 00:29:28.525 align:middle line:90%
This matches that.

00:29:28.525 --> 00:29:31.830 align:middle line:90%


00:29:31.830 --> 00:29:32.330 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:29:32.330 --> 00:29:34.670 align:middle line:84%
So this here
represents lines that

00:29:34.670 --> 00:29:38.090 align:middle line:84%
contain at least two points,
and this represents lines

00:29:38.090 --> 00:29:41.210 align:middle line:90%
that contain only one point.

00:29:41.210 --> 00:29:42.090 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:29:42.090 --> 00:29:49.115 align:middle line:84%
And now the key point that
that is smaller than that.

00:29:49.115 --> 00:29:54.240 align:middle line:90%


00:29:54.240 --> 00:29:55.490 align:middle line:90%
So what are we counting here?

00:29:55.490 --> 00:30:00.050 align:middle line:84%
For each line, we're considering
pairs of points on that line.

00:30:00.050 --> 00:30:03.490 align:middle line:84%
But you can also think you could
sum over all the pairs of points

00:30:03.490 --> 00:30:07.750 align:middle line:84%
and then ask how many
lines go through that pair.

00:30:07.750 --> 00:30:10.150 align:middle line:84%
And there are at most
this many pairs of points

00:30:10.150 --> 00:30:12.325 align:middle line:84%
and for each one of them,
there's only one line.

00:30:12.325 --> 00:30:13.575 align:middle line:90%
So that's the double counting.

00:30:13.575 --> 00:30:18.730 align:middle line:90%


00:30:18.730 --> 00:30:24.550 align:middle line:84%
So this here is the
number of X1, X2 and L

00:30:24.550 --> 00:30:32.050 align:middle line:84%
so that X1 and X2 are on L. And
if you count the lines first

00:30:32.050 --> 00:30:35.660 align:middle line:84%
and then add up over the
lines, you get this expression.

00:30:35.660 --> 00:30:38.500 align:middle line:84%
But if you fix X1
and X2 first, there

00:30:38.500 --> 00:30:40.830 align:middle line:84%
will only be one line
and so you get this.

00:30:40.830 --> 00:30:45.630 align:middle line:90%


00:30:45.630 --> 00:30:46.130 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:30:46.130 --> 00:30:48.438 align:middle line:90%
And now this is that.

00:30:48.438 --> 00:30:49.730 align:middle line:90%
So that's the end of the proof.

00:30:49.730 --> 00:30:54.900 align:middle line:90%


00:30:54.900 --> 00:30:55.400 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:30:55.400 --> 00:30:58.620 align:middle line:90%


00:30:58.620 --> 00:31:02.950 align:middle line:84%
So let's make some remarks
about this simple proof, what

00:31:02.950 --> 00:31:06.220 align:middle line:84%
double counting tells us and
what double counting doesn't

00:31:06.220 --> 00:31:06.780 align:middle line:90%
tell us.

00:31:06.780 --> 00:31:15.040 align:middle line:90%


00:31:15.040 --> 00:31:16.060 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:31:16.060 --> 00:31:26.280 align:middle line:84%
So first, we only used that
two points determine a line.

00:31:26.280 --> 00:31:29.350 align:middle line:90%


00:31:29.350 --> 00:31:31.610 align:middle line:84%
The only fact we used is
that through two points,

00:31:31.610 --> 00:31:33.730 align:middle line:90%
there's only one line.

00:31:33.730 --> 00:31:37.730 align:middle line:84%
So that means that it works
in some more general cases.

00:31:37.730 --> 00:31:41.800 align:middle line:84%
So for instance, it works
for points and lines

00:31:41.800 --> 00:31:42.960 align:middle line:90%
over finite fields.

00:31:42.960 --> 00:31:47.620 align:middle line:90%


00:31:47.620 --> 00:31:49.622 align:middle line:84%
Because over finite
fields, it's still true

00:31:49.622 --> 00:31:51.705 align:middle line:84%
that through any two points
there's only one line.

00:31:51.705 --> 00:31:55.370 align:middle line:90%


00:31:55.370 --> 00:31:59.850 align:middle line:84%
And generality is good, but
this is a blessing and a curse

00:31:59.850 --> 00:32:05.100 align:middle line:84%
in this case, because the whole
Szemeredi-Trotter theorem is not

00:32:05.100 --> 00:32:07.590 align:middle line:90%
true over finite fields.

00:32:07.590 --> 00:32:09.310 align:middle line:84%
I'll show you an
example in a second.

00:32:09.310 --> 00:32:14.280 align:middle line:84%
And that means that this proof,
which only uses this fact,

00:32:14.280 --> 00:32:17.850 align:middle line:84%
cannot really be proving the
whole Szemeredi-Trotter theorem.

00:32:17.850 --> 00:32:22.230 align:middle line:84%
So that's remark B. So the
Szemeredi-Trotter Trotter

00:32:22.230 --> 00:32:26.220 align:middle line:90%
theorem is false over Fq2.

00:32:26.220 --> 00:32:30.180 align:middle line:90%


00:32:30.180 --> 00:32:33.300 align:middle line:90%
Here's the example.

00:32:33.300 --> 00:32:39.210 align:middle line:84%
X is the entire plane,
all the points Fq2,

00:32:39.210 --> 00:32:43.950 align:middle line:90%
and L is all of the lines.

00:32:43.950 --> 00:32:45.820 align:middle line:84%
You could take
literally all the lines,

00:32:45.820 --> 00:32:47.910 align:middle line:84%
or you could take
all of the lines y

00:32:47.910 --> 00:32:52.500 align:middle line:84%
equals mx plus b, where
m and b are in Fq.

00:32:52.500 --> 00:32:55.610 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't matter
very much which one.

00:32:55.610 --> 00:32:56.374 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:32:56.374 --> 00:32:59.540 align:middle line:90%
So size of X is q squared.

00:32:59.540 --> 00:33:02.960 align:middle line:90%
The size of L is q squared.

00:33:02.960 --> 00:33:05.400 align:middle line:84%
And how many
incidences do we have?

00:33:05.400 --> 00:33:08.150 align:middle line:90%
Well, each line has q points.

00:33:08.150 --> 00:33:17.515 align:middle line:84%
So incidences between X and L
is q times L which is q cubed.

00:33:17.515 --> 00:33:20.780 align:middle line:90%


00:33:20.780 --> 00:33:22.175 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:33:22.175 --> 00:33:26.420 align:middle line:84%
So this example is
sharp for lemma one.

00:33:26.420 --> 00:33:30.530 align:middle line:90%
That's equal to XL to the 1/2.

00:33:30.530 --> 00:33:32.340 align:middle line:90%
That matches that term up there.

00:33:32.340 --> 00:33:34.910 align:middle line:84%
And it's much bigger
than the right-hand side

00:33:34.910 --> 00:33:36.240 align:middle line:90%
of Szemeredi-Trotter.

00:33:36.240 --> 00:33:39.135 align:middle line:90%


00:33:39.135 --> 00:33:39.635 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:33:39.635 --> 00:33:40.135 align:middle line:90%
OK, yeah.

00:33:40.135 --> 00:33:41.370 align:middle line:90%
So let's do a little algebra.

00:33:41.370 --> 00:33:44.970 align:middle line:84%
So we have here an X
times L to the 1/2.

00:33:44.970 --> 00:33:50.030 align:middle line:84%
In Szemeredi-Trotter, we have
an X to the 2/3, L to the 2/3.

00:33:50.030 --> 00:33:54.400 align:middle line:84%
So there are different regimes
about who dominates there.

00:33:54.400 --> 00:33:57.470 align:middle line:84%
But this thing is always
bigger than this thing,

00:33:57.470 --> 00:33:58.770 align:middle line:90%
and it's usually much bigger.

00:33:58.770 --> 00:34:02.770 align:middle line:90%


00:34:02.770 --> 00:34:06.610 align:middle line:84%
So here, X times L to
the half is q cubed.

00:34:06.610 --> 00:34:13.750 align:middle line:84%
X to the 2/3, L to the
2/3 would be q to the 8/3,

00:34:13.750 --> 00:34:16.750 align:middle line:84%
which is much less than
the number of incidences.

00:34:16.750 --> 00:34:20.190 align:middle line:84%
So the Szemeredi-Trotter bound
does not hold in this example.

00:34:20.190 --> 00:34:30.815 align:middle line:90%


00:34:30.815 --> 00:34:31.315 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:34:31.315 --> 00:34:33.429 align:middle line:84%
So that shows something
important about

00:34:33.429 --> 00:34:37.179 align:middle line:84%
the Szemeredi-Trotter theorem,
that we cannot prove it just

00:34:37.179 --> 00:34:39.889 align:middle line:84%
by using the fact that two
points determine a line

00:34:39.889 --> 00:34:43.190 align:middle line:84%
and doing our double counting in
a very clever, complicated way.

00:34:43.190 --> 00:34:46.300 align:middle line:90%
We genuinely need another input.

00:34:46.300 --> 00:34:49.120 align:middle line:84%
And all of the proofs of
Szemeredi-Trotter theorem

00:34:49.120 --> 00:34:52.590 align:middle line:84%
use somehow the
topology of the plane.

00:34:52.590 --> 00:35:01.050 align:middle line:84%
So see all proofs of
Szemeredi-Trotter use

00:35:01.050 --> 00:35:06.510 align:middle line:84%
the topology of the
plane in some way.

00:35:06.510 --> 00:35:08.160 align:middle line:84%
And the topology
of R2 is kind of

00:35:08.160 --> 00:35:12.270 align:middle line:84%
different from the topology of
Fq2, whatever that might mean.

00:35:12.270 --> 00:35:14.220 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:35:14.220 --> 00:35:15.040 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:35:15.040 --> 00:35:17.070 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:35:17.070 --> 00:35:19.447 align:middle line:84%
So I know four
different proofs of--

00:35:19.447 --> 00:35:21.780 align:middle line:84%
I've seen four different
proofs of the Szemeredi-Trotter

00:35:21.780 --> 00:35:24.270 align:middle line:84%
theorem, and they use topology
in some different ways.

00:35:24.270 --> 00:35:25.930 align:middle line:90%
I'll show you just one.

00:35:25.930 --> 00:35:28.680 align:middle line:90%
I think it's probably the one--

00:35:28.680 --> 00:35:31.180 align:middle line:84%
the proofs are not that
different from each other.

00:35:31.180 --> 00:35:35.040 align:middle line:84%
I think this probably
is the one that

00:35:35.040 --> 00:35:37.530 align:middle line:84%
is the most convenient for
thinking about projection

00:35:37.530 --> 00:35:39.250 align:middle line:90%
theory for balls in R2.

00:35:39.250 --> 00:35:39.750 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:35:39.750 --> 00:35:41.680 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: You're saying
Szemeredi-Trotter,

00:35:41.680 --> 00:35:44.237 align:middle line:84%
but you always mean this one
on the lower board, not the--

00:35:44.237 --> 00:35:45.070 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:35:45.070 --> 00:35:45.640 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:35:45.640 --> 00:35:46.530 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:35:46.530 --> 00:35:47.160 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:35:47.160 --> 00:35:50.267 align:middle line:90%
So we'll prove this theorem.

00:35:50.267 --> 00:35:52.350 align:middle line:84%
It's not too hard to see
that this theorem implies

00:35:52.350 --> 00:35:53.280 align:middle line:90%
the one on the top.

00:35:53.280 --> 00:35:53.780 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:35:53.780 --> 00:35:56.115 align:middle line:90%


00:35:56.115 --> 00:35:56.615 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:35:56.615 --> 00:35:59.490 align:middle line:90%


00:35:59.490 --> 00:36:00.330 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:36:00.330 --> 00:36:02.040 align:middle line:84%
So the proof I'm
going to show you

00:36:02.040 --> 00:36:06.630 align:middle line:84%
is based on cutting
the plane into pieces.

00:36:06.630 --> 00:36:13.560 align:middle line:84%
And it goes back to work of
Clarkson, Guibas, Edelsbrunner,

00:36:13.560 --> 00:36:16.320 align:middle line:90%
Sharir, and Welzl.

00:36:16.320 --> 00:36:18.600 align:middle line:84%
It's not the very
first proof, but I

00:36:18.600 --> 00:36:21.000 align:middle line:90%
think it's a very nice proof.

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:23.040 align:middle line:84%
And then it's a
slightly revised version

00:36:23.040 --> 00:36:26.620 align:middle line:84%
of that that Nets
Katz and I worked on.

00:36:26.620 --> 00:36:27.120 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:36:27.120 --> 00:36:30.040 align:middle line:84%
So it's based on cutting
the plane into pieces.

00:36:30.040 --> 00:36:33.275 align:middle line:84%
So let me say what I mean
by that by stating a lemma.

00:36:33.275 --> 00:36:42.780 align:middle line:90%


00:36:42.780 --> 00:36:44.160 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:36:44.160 --> 00:36:57.560 align:middle line:84%
So cell decomposition
lemma says that if X

00:36:57.560 --> 00:37:04.880 align:middle line:84%
is a finite subset of the plane
and S is a natural number,

00:37:04.880 --> 00:37:08.810 align:middle line:84%
then there's a way
to cut up the plane.

00:37:08.810 --> 00:37:15.440 align:middle line:84%
So I think of it as a cell
wall and then a bunch of cells.

00:37:15.440 --> 00:37:20.660 align:middle line:84%
So each one of these is open,
and I'll call it a cell.

00:37:20.660 --> 00:37:25.250 align:middle line:84%
And this set W is
closed and I'll call it

00:37:25.250 --> 00:37:27.530 align:middle line:90%
the wall between the cells.

00:37:27.530 --> 00:37:31.760 align:middle line:84%
So the image here is
that I have some points.

00:37:31.760 --> 00:37:38.300 align:middle line:84%
So that's X. And then I
have something like this.

00:37:38.300 --> 00:37:41.660 align:middle line:84%
That's W. And this is
01, 02, 03, and 04.

00:37:41.660 --> 00:37:44.480 align:middle line:90%


00:37:44.480 --> 00:37:44.980 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:37:44.980 --> 00:37:48.690 align:middle line:90%


00:37:48.690 --> 00:37:49.190 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:37:49.190 --> 00:37:51.610 align:middle line:90%
So it has some properties.

00:37:51.610 --> 00:37:53.410 align:middle line:90%
Number one.

00:37:53.410 --> 00:38:03.280 align:middle line:84%
Each line intersects
at most around S cells.

00:38:03.280 --> 00:38:07.000 align:middle line:84%
And also, the line
can intersect the wall

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:09.795 align:middle line:90%
but in at most around S points.

00:38:09.795 --> 00:38:15.610 align:middle line:90%


00:38:15.610 --> 00:38:16.801 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:38:16.801 --> 00:38:22.690 align:middle line:84%
And then each cell in
the cell decomposition

00:38:22.690 --> 00:38:27.165 align:middle line:84%
has at most X over
S squared points.

00:38:27.165 --> 00:38:34.300 align:middle line:90%


00:38:34.300 --> 00:38:35.260 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:38:35.260 --> 00:38:40.540 align:middle line:84%
Now it's not very
obvious yet where

00:38:40.540 --> 00:38:42.050 align:middle line:90%
all these formulas came from.

00:38:42.050 --> 00:38:44.760 align:middle line:84%
And it's definitely not
obvious how to prove this,

00:38:44.760 --> 00:38:47.940 align:middle line:84%
but it's pretty easy to
prove this in the example

00:38:47.940 --> 00:38:51.820 align:middle line:84%
that X is approximately
like a square grid.

00:38:51.820 --> 00:38:54.270 align:middle line:84%
So let me just show you
that as a motivation

00:38:54.270 --> 00:38:55.670 align:middle line:90%
for where this might come from.

00:38:55.670 --> 00:38:58.740 align:middle line:90%


00:38:58.740 --> 00:39:01.685 align:middle line:84%
And to help digest
what the lemma says.

00:39:01.685 --> 00:39:05.244 align:middle line:90%


00:39:05.244 --> 00:39:08.110 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:39:08.110 --> 00:39:09.942 align:middle line:90%


00:39:09.942 --> 00:39:10.860 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Ah.

00:39:10.860 --> 00:39:11.620 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:39:11.620 --> 00:39:14.760 align:middle line:90%
So, right.

00:39:14.760 --> 00:39:20.040 align:middle line:84%
So the comment is I didn't say
anything about a set of lines.

00:39:20.040 --> 00:39:25.500 align:middle line:84%
So what this means
is for every line L.

00:39:25.500 --> 00:39:31.440 align:middle line:84%
And here, this is for every line
L. Now if we had a set of lines,

00:39:31.440 --> 00:39:33.690 align:middle line:84%
all we would really need is
to have this for the lines

00:39:33.690 --> 00:39:34.617 align:middle line:90%
from our set of lines.

00:39:34.617 --> 00:39:36.950 align:middle line:84%
But in practice, it's actually
just true for every line.

00:39:36.950 --> 00:39:40.740 align:middle line:90%


00:39:40.740 --> 00:39:41.240 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:39:41.240 --> 00:39:50.840 align:middle line:90%


00:39:50.840 --> 00:39:51.630 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:39:51.630 --> 00:39:53.750 align:middle line:84%
So the cell decomposition
lemma, in general,

00:39:53.750 --> 00:39:56.850 align:middle line:84%
is somewhat difficult.
We'll talk about the proof.

00:39:56.850 --> 00:39:59.480 align:middle line:84%
But let me show you an
easy case that I hope

00:39:59.480 --> 00:40:01.500 align:middle line:90%
will motivate the statement.

00:40:01.500 --> 00:40:02.000 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:04.850 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: You want X to
not intersect the wall?

00:40:04.850 --> 00:40:07.820 align:middle line:84%
It looks like you just
put X in the wall.

00:40:07.820 --> 00:40:12.620 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: It looks like we
could just put X in the wall.

00:40:12.620 --> 00:40:13.585 align:middle line:90%
Let's see here.

00:40:13.585 --> 00:40:17.970 align:middle line:90%


00:40:17.970 --> 00:40:18.470 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:40:18.470 --> 00:40:22.310 align:middle line:84%
So another comment
is that X is allowed

00:40:22.310 --> 00:40:24.210 align:middle line:90%
to be a subset of the wall.

00:40:24.210 --> 00:40:27.650 align:middle line:84%
And that sounds a
little suspicious.

00:40:27.650 --> 00:40:32.480 align:middle line:84%
But we do get something from
that because every line only

00:40:32.480 --> 00:40:34.650 align:middle line:90%
hits the wall in S points.

00:40:34.650 --> 00:40:37.170 align:middle line:84%
So if x were a
subset of the wall,

00:40:37.170 --> 00:40:40.620 align:middle line:84%
then every line would
only hit X in S points,

00:40:40.620 --> 00:40:43.280 align:middle line:84%
and that would be a
useful tool for us.

00:40:43.280 --> 00:40:45.960 align:middle line:84%
Also remember that
S is a parameter.

00:40:45.960 --> 00:40:49.040 align:middle line:84%
So for each S, there's
a way of doing this.

00:40:49.040 --> 00:40:52.040 align:middle line:84%
We're going to eventually--
we'll look at our set of points

00:40:52.040 --> 00:40:53.540 align:middle line:84%
and our set of
lines, and then we'll

00:40:53.540 --> 00:40:55.610 align:middle line:90%
pick an S that's strategic.

00:40:55.610 --> 00:40:58.810 align:middle line:84%
So if S is small, this
is really quite strong.

00:40:58.810 --> 00:41:02.270 align:middle line:90%


00:41:02.270 --> 00:41:05.042 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:41:05.042 --> 00:41:16.555 align:middle line:84%
So here's an example is that
X is roughly a square grid.

00:41:16.555 --> 00:41:19.070 align:middle line:90%


00:41:19.070 --> 00:41:21.030 align:middle line:84%
So let me make
that more precise.

00:41:21.030 --> 00:41:24.860 align:middle line:84%
Let's say X is contained
in 0 to N squared,

00:41:24.860 --> 00:41:31.135 align:middle line:84%
and X intersected with a unit
ball around any center is small.

00:41:31.135 --> 00:41:34.160 align:middle line:90%


00:41:34.160 --> 00:41:40.480 align:middle line:84%
And let's say that there are
around N squared points in X.

00:41:40.480 --> 00:41:44.080 align:middle line:90%
So what does this X look like?

00:41:44.080 --> 00:41:45.615 align:middle line:90%
We have an N by N box.

00:41:45.615 --> 00:41:48.410 align:middle line:90%


00:41:48.410 --> 00:41:48.910 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:41:48.910 --> 00:41:52.785 align:middle line:84%
Let me imagine cutting it like a
checkerboard into unit squares.

00:41:52.785 --> 00:41:59.590 align:middle line:90%


00:41:59.590 --> 00:42:04.630 align:middle line:84%
And this tells me that I have
on the order of 1 point of X

00:42:04.630 --> 00:42:05.715 align:middle line:90%
in each unit square.

00:42:05.715 --> 00:42:09.880 align:middle line:90%


00:42:09.880 --> 00:42:13.510 align:middle line:90%
So this is a class of sets.

00:42:13.510 --> 00:42:17.380 align:middle line:84%
So I call this is
roughly a square grid.

00:42:17.380 --> 00:42:17.930 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:42:17.930 --> 00:42:21.250 align:middle line:90%
So now how would we cut it up?

00:42:21.250 --> 00:42:24.420 align:middle line:90%
I cut it up like this.

00:42:24.420 --> 00:42:27.310 align:middle line:90%


00:42:27.310 --> 00:42:37.920 align:middle line:84%
I'll do N over S. So the
wall is S vertical lines

00:42:37.920 --> 00:42:40.295 align:middle line:90%
union with S horizontal lines.

00:42:40.295 --> 00:42:49.260 align:middle line:90%


00:42:49.260 --> 00:42:49.760 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:42:49.760 --> 00:42:56.710 align:middle line:90%


00:42:56.710 --> 00:43:00.760 align:middle line:84%
So the wall cuts it
into S squared pieces,

00:43:00.760 --> 00:43:03.600 align:middle line:84%
and because my set is
distributed so evenly,

00:43:03.600 --> 00:43:06.010 align:middle line:84%
each of these pieces
has about the same size.

00:43:06.010 --> 00:43:10.200 align:middle line:84%
So that gives me
the third bullet.

00:43:10.200 --> 00:43:14.070 align:middle line:84%
And if we were to make
a line in this picture,

00:43:14.070 --> 00:43:19.050 align:middle line:84%
well, it can only cross each
of these other lines once.

00:43:19.050 --> 00:43:22.950 align:middle line:84%
So a line will intersect
the wall at most 2S times.

00:43:22.950 --> 00:43:26.380 align:middle line:84%
And to go from one
cell to another cell,

00:43:26.380 --> 00:43:27.520 align:middle line:90%
it has to cross the wall.

00:43:27.520 --> 00:43:30.290 align:middle line:90%
So only enter about 2S cells.

00:43:30.290 --> 00:43:33.860 align:middle line:90%


00:43:33.860 --> 00:43:34.760 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:43:34.760 --> 00:43:40.450 align:middle line:84%
So the bullets are
not hard to check.

00:43:40.450 --> 00:43:52.725 align:middle line:90%


00:43:52.725 --> 00:43:53.225 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:43:53.225 --> 00:43:58.640 align:middle line:90%


00:43:58.640 --> 00:43:59.140 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:43:59.140 --> 00:44:03.380 align:middle line:90%


00:44:03.380 --> 00:44:08.600 align:middle line:84%
So this decomposition method
is based on the key observation

00:44:08.600 --> 00:44:12.390 align:middle line:84%
that it's actually helpful to
cut up our problem like this,

00:44:12.390 --> 00:44:14.630 align:middle line:84%
cut up our space like
this, and then count

00:44:14.630 --> 00:44:17.390 align:middle line:84%
the incidences in
each cell separately

00:44:17.390 --> 00:44:20.570 align:middle line:90%
and the incidences on the wall.

00:44:20.570 --> 00:44:23.900 align:middle line:84%
And in each of those pieces,
we can use our double counting

00:44:23.900 --> 00:44:24.570 align:middle line:90%
argument.

00:44:24.570 --> 00:44:25.950 align:middle line:84%
But when we add
it up at the end,

00:44:25.950 --> 00:44:28.367 align:middle line:84%
we may get something better
than using the double counting

00:44:28.367 --> 00:44:29.230 align:middle line:90%
argument globally.

00:44:29.230 --> 00:44:39.950 align:middle line:90%


00:44:39.950 --> 00:44:40.450 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:44:40.450 --> 00:44:54.040 align:middle line:90%


00:44:54.040 --> 00:44:54.590 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:44:54.590 --> 00:44:57.345 align:middle line:84%
So proof of theorem two,
assuming this lemma.

00:44:57.345 --> 00:45:01.180 align:middle line:90%


00:45:01.180 --> 00:45:01.850 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:45:01.850 --> 00:45:09.790 align:middle line:84%
So we're given X and L,
and S is going to be TBD.

00:45:09.790 --> 00:45:12.970 align:middle line:90%
And we can apply this thing.

00:45:12.970 --> 00:45:13.970 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:13.970 --> 00:45:21.490 align:middle line:84%
So let's say that Xi is
X intersected with Oi.

00:45:21.490 --> 00:45:25.120 align:middle line:84%
Then we can say
that Xi is less than

00:45:25.120 --> 00:45:28.760 align:middle line:84%
or equal to less sim
X over S squared.

00:45:28.760 --> 00:45:30.830 align:middle line:84%
That was given to us
as a bullet point.

00:45:30.830 --> 00:45:34.840 align:middle line:84%
And the sum over i
of Xi is at most X,

00:45:34.840 --> 00:45:37.750 align:middle line:90%
because these are disjoint sets.

00:45:37.750 --> 00:45:39.526 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:39.526 --> 00:45:43.900 align:middle line:84%
Now let's say that Li
is the set of lines

00:45:43.900 --> 00:45:46.395 align:middle line:90%
that intersect the cell Oi.

00:45:46.395 --> 00:45:52.450 align:middle line:90%


00:45:52.450 --> 00:45:53.310 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:53.310 --> 00:45:54.710 align:middle line:90%
Now these are disjoint.

00:45:54.710 --> 00:45:56.740 align:middle line:90%
Each point is only in one cell.

00:45:56.740 --> 00:46:02.360 align:middle line:84%
These are not disjoint because
a line goes through many cells.

00:46:02.360 --> 00:46:05.680 align:middle line:84%
So this blue line
belongs to Li for this i

00:46:05.680 --> 00:46:10.690 align:middle line:84%
and this i and this i, but not
for this i or this i or that i.

00:46:10.690 --> 00:46:11.604 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:46:11.604 --> 00:46:16.630 align:middle line:84%
So if you add up over
i, the size of Li,

00:46:16.630 --> 00:46:19.900 align:middle line:84%
that is bounded by S
times the size of L,

00:46:19.900 --> 00:46:25.990 align:middle line:84%
because each line in L
belongs to at most S cells.

00:46:25.990 --> 00:46:26.900 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:46:26.900 --> 00:46:30.810 align:middle line:84%
So now let's count
our incidences.

00:46:30.810 --> 00:46:35.735 align:middle line:84%
So there are incidences
from each cell.

00:46:35.735 --> 00:46:41.160 align:middle line:90%


00:46:41.160 --> 00:46:43.470 align:middle line:84%
And the incidences
related to the i-th cell

00:46:43.470 --> 00:46:45.720 align:middle line:84%
have points from the
i-th cell and they have

00:46:45.720 --> 00:46:48.540 align:middle line:90%
lines that enter the i-th cell.

00:46:48.540 --> 00:46:51.840 align:middle line:84%
There also are incidences
involving the wall.

00:46:51.840 --> 00:47:00.270 align:middle line:84%
So add the incidences from X
intersected with the wall and L.

00:47:00.270 --> 00:47:01.230 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:47:01.230 --> 00:47:03.540 align:middle line:84%
Now we apply our
double counting lemma

00:47:03.540 --> 00:47:06.480 align:middle line:84%
to estimate each
of these things.

00:47:06.480 --> 00:47:15.240 align:middle line:84%
So that's less than the sum
on i Xi Li to the 1/2 plus Li.

00:47:15.240 --> 00:47:18.330 align:middle line:90%


00:47:18.330 --> 00:47:22.810 align:middle line:84%
And for the wall, well, each
line only hits the wall S times.

00:47:22.810 --> 00:47:25.375 align:middle line:84%
So we have S times
the number of lines.

00:47:25.375 --> 00:47:34.280 align:middle line:90%


00:47:34.280 --> 00:47:34.780 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:47:34.780 --> 00:47:38.750 align:middle line:84%
Now from this point on, we just
do a little bit of algebra.

00:47:38.750 --> 00:47:41.360 align:middle line:84%
We just have an expression
involving these numbers Xi

00:47:41.360 --> 00:47:46.555 align:middle line:84%
and Li, and we know a few
inequalities about Xi and Li.

00:47:46.555 --> 00:47:47.763 align:middle line:90%
We'll just put them together.

00:47:47.763 --> 00:47:51.620 align:middle line:90%


00:47:51.620 --> 00:47:54.980 align:middle line:84%
Here, it's reasonable
to Cauchy-Schwarz

00:47:54.980 --> 00:47:58.290 align:middle line:84%
because I know information
about Xi and Li separately.

00:47:58.290 --> 00:48:05.810 align:middle line:84%
So that will disentangle this,
sum on i Xi squared to the 1/2

00:48:05.810 --> 00:48:10.415 align:middle line:90%
sum on i of Li to the 1/2.

00:48:10.415 --> 00:48:13.460 align:middle line:84%
This sum on Li, I
just read that off,

00:48:13.460 --> 00:48:15.085 align:middle line:84%
and that can be
grouped with that.

00:48:15.085 --> 00:48:18.680 align:middle line:90%


00:48:18.680 --> 00:48:20.384 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:48:20.384 --> 00:48:24.530 align:middle line:84%
And now, what do I do
with this sum of squares?

00:48:24.530 --> 00:48:28.340 align:middle line:84%
Well, I know that each Xi
is bounded by something,

00:48:28.340 --> 00:48:30.640 align:middle line:90%
so I can pull that out.

00:48:30.640 --> 00:48:34.690 align:middle line:84%
So I'll have X over
S squared, and I'll

00:48:34.690 --> 00:48:38.500 align:middle line:90%
have left the sum of Xi.

00:48:38.500 --> 00:48:41.480 align:middle line:84%
This sum of Li,
well, it's just here.

00:48:41.480 --> 00:48:45.470 align:middle line:90%
So it's SL to the 1/2.

00:48:45.470 --> 00:48:48.670 align:middle line:90%
And I copy this.

00:48:48.670 --> 00:48:49.570 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:48:49.570 --> 00:48:54.340 align:middle line:84%
This sum of Xi is
bounded by X. And so then

00:48:54.340 --> 00:48:56.060 align:middle line:90%
I'll do a little algebra here.

00:48:56.060 --> 00:48:58.240 align:middle line:90%
This is the important term.

00:48:58.240 --> 00:49:04.990 align:middle line:84%
I'll have an X squared
to the 1/2, so X and X.

00:49:04.990 --> 00:49:07.990 align:middle line:90%
I have an L to the 1/2.

00:49:07.990 --> 00:49:13.330 align:middle line:84%
And I'll have some powers of S.
There will be 1 over S coming

00:49:13.330 --> 00:49:16.850 align:middle line:84%
from here and an S to the
1/2 coming from there.

00:49:16.850 --> 00:49:21.180 align:middle line:84%
So altogether I have an
S to the negative 1/2.

00:49:21.180 --> 00:49:22.770 align:middle line:90%
And this I'll copy over.

00:49:22.770 --> 00:49:26.570 align:middle line:90%


00:49:26.570 --> 00:49:27.070 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:49:27.070 --> 00:49:29.345 align:middle line:84%
Let's pause there for a
second after the algebra.

00:49:29.345 --> 00:49:39.160 align:middle line:90%


00:49:39.160 --> 00:49:39.660 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:49:39.660 --> 00:49:42.360 align:middle line:84%
So let's take stock of
the bound that we got

00:49:42.360 --> 00:49:47.010 align:middle line:84%
and how it compares to the
double counting argument.

00:49:47.010 --> 00:49:49.650 align:middle line:84%
If you compare this to the
double counting argument,

00:49:49.650 --> 00:49:51.520 align:middle line:90%
the terms match up.

00:49:51.520 --> 00:49:54.580 align:middle line:84%
So the double counting,
we have XL to the 1/2,

00:49:54.580 --> 00:50:00.450 align:middle line:84%
and that first term gets
decreased by S to the minus 1/2

00:50:00.450 --> 00:50:05.400 align:middle line:84%
when we introduce our cutting
and then the second term of L

00:50:05.400 --> 00:50:09.900 align:middle line:90%
gets increased by a factor of S.

00:50:09.900 --> 00:50:13.350 align:middle line:84%
So if originally the
first term dominated,

00:50:13.350 --> 00:50:20.190 align:middle line:84%
then life will get better
when we do this decomposition.

00:50:20.190 --> 00:50:22.390 align:middle line:84%
And if originally
the L dominated,

00:50:22.390 --> 00:50:25.920 align:middle line:84%
then life will not get better
when we do this decomposition.

00:50:25.920 --> 00:50:26.490 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:50:26.490 --> 00:50:27.190 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:50:27.190 --> 00:50:30.930 align:middle line:84%
So at the end here,
we just choose

00:50:30.930 --> 00:50:35.300 align:middle line:84%
S greater than or equal to 1 to
minimize the right-hand side.

00:50:35.300 --> 00:50:38.880 align:middle line:90%


00:50:38.880 --> 00:50:40.930 align:middle line:84%
And if you do a
little bit of algebra,

00:50:40.930 --> 00:50:42.815 align:middle line:84%
you'll get out the
Szemeredi-Trotter bound.

00:50:42.815 --> 00:50:45.480 align:middle line:90%


00:50:45.480 --> 00:50:45.980 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:50:45.980 --> 00:50:52.140 align:middle line:90%


00:50:52.140 --> 00:50:54.300 align:middle line:84%
I remember spending
some time trying

00:50:54.300 --> 00:50:55.920 align:middle line:84%
to digest why
things were getting

00:50:55.920 --> 00:50:58.680 align:middle line:90%
better when we subdivided.

00:50:58.680 --> 00:51:01.260 align:middle line:84%
And here was one
thought I had about it.

00:51:01.260 --> 00:51:03.370 align:middle line:84%
If you look at the
double counting bound,

00:51:03.370 --> 00:51:05.490 align:middle line:84%
there are these
different regimes.

00:51:05.490 --> 00:51:09.850 align:middle line:84%
So there's a regime where
the left term dominates.

00:51:09.850 --> 00:51:12.300 align:middle line:84%
And in that regime, the
double counting bound

00:51:12.300 --> 00:51:14.370 align:middle line:90%
is bigger than the truth.

00:51:14.370 --> 00:51:17.910 align:middle line:84%
And there's a regime where
the right term dominates,

00:51:17.910 --> 00:51:20.868 align:middle line:84%
and you can always have L
incidences, so that's not that--

00:51:20.868 --> 00:51:22.785 align:middle line:84%
when the right term
dominates, it's the truth.

00:51:22.785 --> 00:51:25.380 align:middle line:90%


00:51:25.380 --> 00:51:26.320 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:51:26.320 --> 00:51:28.830 align:middle line:90%
So what are the regimes?

00:51:28.830 --> 00:51:32.400 align:middle line:84%
The right term that the L
dominates if L is bigger than X

00:51:32.400 --> 00:51:34.380 align:middle line:90%
squared.

00:51:34.380 --> 00:51:35.940 align:middle line:84%
So you have a lot
of lines compared

00:51:35.940 --> 00:51:40.320 align:middle line:84%
to the number of points,
then double counting already

00:51:40.320 --> 00:51:42.475 align:middle line:90%
gives a sharp bound.

00:51:42.475 --> 00:51:42.975 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:51:42.975 --> 00:51:46.930 align:middle line:84%
So suppose originally that L
is not bigger than X squared.

00:51:46.930 --> 00:51:49.230 align:middle line:84%
So if I just apply double
counting out of the box,

00:51:49.230 --> 00:51:52.060 align:middle line:84%
the XL to the 1/2
would dominate,

00:51:52.060 --> 00:51:54.270 align:middle line:90%
which I'm not so happy with.

00:51:54.270 --> 00:51:58.150 align:middle line:84%
Then I try cutting
things up into cells.

00:51:58.150 --> 00:52:01.170 align:middle line:84%
I count the incidences
in each cell.

00:52:01.170 --> 00:52:04.350 align:middle line:90%
Is life any better?

00:52:04.350 --> 00:52:08.080 align:middle line:90%
Well, I have S squared cells.

00:52:08.080 --> 00:52:11.140 align:middle line:84%
So if I look-- and the points
are kind of evenly distributed.

00:52:11.140 --> 00:52:14.040 align:middle line:84%
So if I look inside one
cell, the number of points

00:52:14.040 --> 00:52:17.770 align:middle line:84%
goes down by S squared,
which is quite a lot.

00:52:17.770 --> 00:52:19.190 align:middle line:90%
How about lines?

00:52:19.190 --> 00:52:21.560 align:middle line:84%
Well, not every line
goes through this cell,

00:52:21.560 --> 00:52:24.280 align:middle line:84%
so the number of
lines also goes down.

00:52:24.280 --> 00:52:27.980 align:middle line:84%
But because each line
goes through many cells,

00:52:27.980 --> 00:52:31.240 align:middle line:84%
each line goes through S
cells, the fraction of lines

00:52:31.240 --> 00:52:33.310 align:middle line:84%
that I would expect to
go through this cell is

00:52:33.310 --> 00:52:37.030 align:middle line:90%
1 over S of all the lines.

00:52:37.030 --> 00:52:39.200 align:middle line:84%
So the number of
points goes down a lot,

00:52:39.200 --> 00:52:42.970 align:middle line:84%
and the number of lines
only goes down a little.

00:52:42.970 --> 00:52:44.890 align:middle line:84%
By doing that,
I'm tilting things

00:52:44.890 --> 00:52:47.990 align:middle line:84%
towards having a lot of
lines and few points.

00:52:47.990 --> 00:52:49.705 align:middle line:90%
And if you think about--

00:52:49.705 --> 00:52:53.860 align:middle line:84%
if you track what is the best
value of this S, what happens

00:52:53.860 --> 00:52:57.040 align:middle line:84%
is the S is best when
we cut it in such a way

00:52:57.040 --> 00:52:59.860 align:middle line:84%
that inside of each
cell, the number of lines

00:52:59.860 --> 00:53:02.200 align:middle line:90%
is the number of points squared.

00:53:02.200 --> 00:53:03.700 align:middle line:84%
And that means the
double counting

00:53:03.700 --> 00:53:06.255 align:middle line:84%
is giving the correct
bound inside of each cell.

00:53:06.255 --> 00:53:16.860 align:middle line:90%


00:53:16.860 --> 00:53:18.600 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:53:18.600 --> 00:53:19.520 align:middle line:90%
Questions or comments?

00:53:19.520 --> 00:53:34.180 align:middle line:90%


00:53:34.180 --> 00:53:34.680 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:53:34.680 --> 00:53:37.740 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk about how to
prove the cell decomposition

00:53:37.740 --> 00:53:41.910 align:middle line:84%
lemma which uses a
little bit of topology.

00:53:41.910 --> 00:53:44.370 align:middle line:84%
So in our cell
decomposition lemma,

00:53:44.370 --> 00:53:49.320 align:middle line:84%
we want to take our points
and cut them up in evenly

00:53:49.320 --> 00:53:50.580 align:middle line:90%
in some way.

00:53:50.580 --> 00:53:53.130 align:middle line:84%
And that is reminiscent
of a classical thing

00:53:53.130 --> 00:53:55.570 align:middle line:84%
in topology called the
ham sandwich theorem.

00:53:55.570 --> 00:54:00.840 align:middle line:84%
And the cell decomposition
lemma is like a variant

00:54:00.840 --> 00:54:02.440 align:middle line:90%
of the ham sandwich theorem.

00:54:02.440 --> 00:54:04.860 align:middle line:84%
So I will first recall
the ham sandwich theorem

00:54:04.860 --> 00:54:10.410 align:middle line:84%
and how to prove that, and
then we'll work up to this.

00:54:10.410 --> 00:54:11.450 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:54:11.450 --> 00:54:15.260 align:middle line:84%
So our starting
point in topology

00:54:15.260 --> 00:54:17.605 align:middle line:84%
is going to be the
Borsuk-Ulam theorem.

00:54:17.605 --> 00:54:20.330 align:middle line:90%


00:54:20.330 --> 00:54:23.730 align:middle line:84%
So I'll recall that,
I'll state that,

00:54:23.730 --> 00:54:25.340 align:middle line:84%
and then we'll try
to prove everything

00:54:25.340 --> 00:54:26.786 align:middle line:90%
else from Borsuk-Ulam.

00:54:26.786 --> 00:54:38.840 align:middle line:90%


00:54:38.840 --> 00:54:39.430 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:54:39.430 --> 00:54:44.120 align:middle line:90%


00:54:44.120 --> 00:54:47.090 align:middle line:84%
So the Borsuk-Ulam
theorem says that if you

00:54:47.090 --> 00:54:49.310 align:middle line:84%
have a function
from the N sphere

00:54:49.310 --> 00:54:54.810 align:middle line:84%
to RN, which is continuous,
and its antipodal.

00:54:54.810 --> 00:54:57.200 align:middle line:84%
So that means f
of negative theta

00:54:57.200 --> 00:55:02.300 align:middle line:84%
is negative f of theta for
every theta in the sphere.

00:55:02.300 --> 00:55:08.270 align:middle line:84%
Then the conclusion is that
0 is in the image of f,

00:55:08.270 --> 00:55:11.425 align:middle line:84%
there is some point in the
sphere that got mapped to zero.

00:55:11.425 --> 00:55:19.650 align:middle line:90%


00:55:19.650 --> 00:55:20.150 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:55:20.150 --> 00:55:25.430 align:middle line:90%


00:55:25.430 --> 00:55:26.330 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:55:26.330 --> 00:55:29.120 align:middle line:84%
So as a corollary
of that, we're going

00:55:29.120 --> 00:55:31.255 align:middle line:90%
to do the ham sandwich theorem.

00:55:31.255 --> 00:55:36.710 align:middle line:90%


00:55:36.710 --> 00:55:39.200 align:middle line:84%
So one version of the
ham sandwich theorem

00:55:39.200 --> 00:55:44.960 align:middle line:84%
says that if O1 up
to On contained in RN

00:55:44.960 --> 00:55:46.555 align:middle line:90%
are bounded open sets.

00:55:46.555 --> 00:55:49.790 align:middle line:90%


00:55:49.790 --> 00:55:55.380 align:middle line:84%
Then there exists a hyperplane
h that bisects them all.

00:55:55.380 --> 00:56:06.620 align:middle line:90%


00:56:06.620 --> 00:56:11.450 align:middle line:84%
So for instance, if I had two
bounded open sets in the plane,

00:56:11.450 --> 00:56:16.335 align:middle line:84%
there would be a line somewhere
that bisects both of these sets.

00:56:16.335 --> 00:56:21.820 align:middle line:90%


00:56:21.820 --> 00:56:23.056 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:56:23.056 --> 00:56:25.690 align:middle line:90%
So proof.

00:56:25.690 --> 00:56:29.350 align:middle line:84%
So first we need to
parameterize our choice

00:56:29.350 --> 00:56:31.300 align:middle line:90%
of all the hyperplanes.

00:56:31.300 --> 00:56:33.280 align:middle line:84%
And a good way to
think about that

00:56:33.280 --> 00:56:39.280 align:middle line:84%
is that a hyperplane is
related to a linear function,

00:56:39.280 --> 00:56:42.200 align:middle line:90%
so this is a hyperplane.

00:56:42.200 --> 00:56:46.810 align:middle line:84%
I also am going to want a
hyperplane and one side of it.

00:56:46.810 --> 00:56:49.180 align:middle line:84%
I'll pay attention to
which side is which.

00:56:49.180 --> 00:56:56.980 align:middle line:84%
So this shaded region would
be the region a1, x1 plus an,

00:56:56.980 --> 00:57:00.520 align:middle line:90%
xn is bigger than b.

00:57:00.520 --> 00:57:03.770 align:middle line:84%
So one side of a hyperplane can
always be described that way.

00:57:03.770 --> 00:57:07.030 align:middle line:84%
And we have the
freedom to scale.

00:57:07.030 --> 00:57:13.120 align:middle line:84%
So let's say that theta
is a1 up to an comma b.

00:57:13.120 --> 00:57:16.210 align:middle line:84%
That could be in the N sphere
by scaling theta, which

00:57:16.210 --> 00:57:20.080 align:middle line:90%
doesn't change the hyperplane.

00:57:20.080 --> 00:57:21.976 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:57:21.976 --> 00:57:23.720 align:middle line:90%
So those are my hyperplanes.

00:57:23.720 --> 00:57:25.425 align:middle line:90%
And now f of theta.

00:57:25.425 --> 00:57:31.420 align:middle line:90%


00:57:31.420 --> 00:57:32.720 align:middle line:90%
Here, let me say it this way.

00:57:32.720 --> 00:57:36.580 align:middle line:84%
This guy plus b is
bigger than zero.

00:57:36.580 --> 00:57:49.090 align:middle line:84%
And this thing here, I will
call L sub theta of X. OK.

00:57:49.090 --> 00:57:51.130 align:middle line:90%
So f of theta is--

00:57:51.130 --> 00:57:56.860 align:middle line:84%
f sub i of theta is the
volume of Oi intersect L theta

00:57:56.860 --> 00:57:58.810 align:middle line:90%
is bigger than zero.

00:57:58.810 --> 00:58:05.450 align:middle line:84%
That's the volume of Oi on this
side minus the volume of Oi

00:58:05.450 --> 00:58:08.245 align:middle line:84%
and L sub theta is
smaller than zero.

00:58:08.245 --> 00:58:11.810 align:middle line:90%


00:58:11.810 --> 00:58:15.920 align:middle line:84%
So fi of theta is the
volume of this part of Oi

00:58:15.920 --> 00:58:18.020 align:middle line:84%
minus the volume
of that part of Oi.

00:58:18.020 --> 00:58:21.290 align:middle line:90%


00:58:21.290 --> 00:58:22.070 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:58:22.070 --> 00:58:26.660 align:middle line:84%
So notice that fi
of theta is zero

00:58:26.660 --> 00:58:32.800 align:middle line:84%
if and only if the hyperplane
associated to theta bisects Oi.

00:58:32.800 --> 00:58:38.900 align:middle line:90%


00:58:38.900 --> 00:58:40.286 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:58:40.286 --> 00:58:45.230 align:middle line:90%
Also, fi is antipodal.

00:58:45.230 --> 00:58:50.150 align:middle line:84%
fi of minus theta is
negative fi of theta.

00:58:50.150 --> 00:58:55.010 align:middle line:84%
Because if I replace
theta by minus theta,

00:58:55.010 --> 00:58:57.600 align:middle line:84%
I take the minus of
all these coefficients.

00:58:57.600 --> 00:59:01.190 align:middle line:84%
Then I'm replacing L of
theta by negative L of theta.

00:59:01.190 --> 00:59:04.490 align:middle line:90%
And so that switches who--

00:59:04.490 --> 00:59:07.677 align:middle line:84%
so I have the same zero set,
the same hyperplane, but now

00:59:07.677 --> 00:59:10.010 align:middle line:84%
this one will be positive and
that one will be negative.

00:59:10.010 --> 00:59:12.850 align:middle line:84%
So I'll switch these two
things, which reverses

00:59:12.850 --> 00:59:14.520 align:middle line:90%
the sign of fi of theta.

00:59:14.520 --> 00:59:20.105 align:middle line:90%


00:59:20.105 --> 00:59:20.605 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:59:20.605 --> 00:59:23.860 align:middle line:90%


00:59:23.860 --> 00:59:26.560 align:middle line:90%
fi is also continuous.

00:59:26.560 --> 00:59:30.340 align:middle line:84%
So if I adjust
theta, then I'll make

00:59:30.340 --> 00:59:32.360 align:middle line:90%
a small motion of this plane.

00:59:32.360 --> 00:59:35.560 align:middle line:84%
And that will change these
volumes but only continuously

00:59:35.560 --> 00:59:40.300 align:middle line:84%
because the sets are
bounded and open.

00:59:40.300 --> 00:59:41.908 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:59:41.908 --> 00:59:47.710 align:middle line:84%
So finally I'll make f by just
putting together all these fn's.

00:59:47.710 --> 00:59:52.700 align:middle line:84%
And so f is a function
from the N sphere to RN,

00:59:52.700 --> 00:59:55.836 align:middle line:84%
and it's continuous
and it's antipodal.

00:59:55.836 --> 00:59:58.540 align:middle line:90%


00:59:58.540 --> 01:00:01.480 align:middle line:90%
So the conclusion is--

01:00:01.480 --> 01:00:04.700 align:middle line:84%
so then Borsuk-Ulam tells me
that there exists some theta

01:00:04.700 --> 01:00:07.400 align:middle line:90%
so that f of theta is zero.

01:00:07.400 --> 01:00:11.415 align:middle line:84%
And that means that h theta
bisects all these sets.

01:00:11.415 --> 01:00:18.695 align:middle line:90%


01:00:18.695 --> 01:00:19.195 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:00:19.195 --> 01:00:25.990 align:middle line:90%


01:00:25.990 --> 01:00:26.540 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:00:26.540 --> 01:00:31.240 align:middle line:84%
Now this by itself is not going
to be super helpful for us.

01:00:31.240 --> 01:00:33.980 align:middle line:84%
We have a set that
lives in the plane.

01:00:33.980 --> 01:00:36.880 align:middle line:84%
So the theorem says,
I can find a line

01:00:36.880 --> 01:00:40.480 align:middle line:90%
that bisects any two things.

01:00:40.480 --> 01:00:43.210 align:middle line:84%
I'm hoping to take
a complicated set

01:00:43.210 --> 01:00:45.680 align:middle line:84%
and cut it into
many even pieces.

01:00:45.680 --> 01:00:47.890 align:middle line:84%
And so a more
relevant warm up is

01:00:47.890 --> 01:00:53.290 align:middle line:84%
some way of bisecting
many sets, not just two.

01:00:53.290 --> 01:00:54.234 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:00:54.234 --> 01:00:58.530 align:middle line:84%
So if I put more open
sets here, then there

01:00:58.530 --> 01:01:01.290 align:middle line:84%
will not be a hyperplane
that bisects all of them.

01:01:01.290 --> 01:01:07.570 align:middle line:84%
But I could be more flexible
about what cut I would allow.

01:01:07.570 --> 01:01:09.010 align:middle line:90%
So it can't be a hyperplane.

01:01:09.010 --> 01:01:10.900 align:middle line:84%
It has to be a little
bit more complicated.

01:01:10.900 --> 01:01:14.430 align:middle line:84%
And it turns out to be a
reasonable idea to consider cuts

01:01:14.430 --> 01:01:17.280 align:middle line:90%
by polynomials of some degree.

01:01:17.280 --> 01:01:21.600 align:middle line:84%
So there's a natural
generalization of this.

01:01:21.600 --> 01:01:23.620 align:middle line:84%
You could do really
any class of functions,

01:01:23.620 --> 01:01:26.370 align:middle line:84%
but for this application,
polynomials are useful.

01:01:26.370 --> 01:01:28.490 align:middle line:84%
It's called the polynomial
ham sandwich theorem.

01:01:28.490 --> 01:01:33.450 align:middle line:90%


01:01:33.450 --> 01:01:33.950 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:01:33.950 --> 01:01:53.190 align:middle line:90%


01:01:53.190 --> 01:01:54.210 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:01:54.210 --> 01:02:04.220 align:middle line:84%
So here's a more general
version polynomial ham sandwich.

01:02:04.220 --> 01:02:04.890 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:02:04.890 --> 01:02:09.800 align:middle line:84%
So let's say polynomials
of degree D in RN

01:02:09.800 --> 01:02:16.190 align:middle line:84%
that is the set of polynomials--
so polynomials in N variables

01:02:16.190 --> 01:02:20.960 align:middle line:84%
over R so that the
degree is at most D.

01:02:20.960 --> 01:02:29.510 align:middle line:84%
And so this is a
vector space and it

01:02:29.510 --> 01:02:34.510 align:middle line:84%
has dimension
approximately D to the N

01:02:34.510 --> 01:02:38.070 align:middle line:84%
if the dimension N is fixed and
the degree is going to infinity.

01:02:38.070 --> 01:02:44.540 align:middle line:90%


01:02:44.540 --> 01:02:46.290 align:middle line:84%
The dimension is not
hard to figure out.

01:02:46.290 --> 01:02:53.620 align:middle line:84%
You count how many monomials
are there of degree at most D.

01:02:53.620 --> 01:02:56.410 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:02:56.410 --> 01:03:02.350 align:middle line:84%
So the proposition says that
if capital n is strictly

01:03:02.350 --> 01:03:08.170 align:middle line:84%
less than the dimension
of this space,

01:03:08.170 --> 01:03:15.350 align:middle line:84%
then there exists a polynomial
p, the space of polynomials,

01:03:15.350 --> 01:03:20.350 align:middle line:84%
which is nonzero,
and the polynomial

01:03:20.350 --> 01:03:22.840 align:middle line:90%
bisects each of the open sets.

01:03:22.840 --> 01:03:33.340 align:middle line:84%
So let's say fi of p is
defined to be the volume of Oi

01:03:33.340 --> 01:03:38.350 align:middle line:84%
intersect p is positive
minus the volume

01:03:38.350 --> 01:03:49.150 align:middle line:84%
of Oi intersect p is negative,
and fi of p equals 0 for all i

01:03:49.150 --> 01:03:50.190 align:middle line:90%
from 1 up to n.

01:03:50.190 --> 01:03:53.530 align:middle line:90%


01:03:53.530 --> 01:03:55.690 align:middle line:84%
So that's the statement
of the proposition.

01:03:55.690 --> 01:03:57.580 align:middle line:84%
Instead of using
a hyperplane, we

01:03:57.580 --> 01:04:00.100 align:middle line:84%
use a degree D zero
set of a degree D

01:04:00.100 --> 01:04:02.600 align:middle line:90%
polynomial to bisect our sets.

01:04:02.600 --> 01:04:05.200 align:middle line:84%
And then we can
bisect many more sets.

01:04:05.200 --> 01:04:07.390 align:middle line:90%
This is exactly how many.

01:04:07.390 --> 01:04:12.070 align:middle line:84%
As D increases, we have more
degrees of freedom, bigger

01:04:12.070 --> 01:04:14.265 align:middle line:84%
dimension, and we can
bisect more things.

01:04:14.265 --> 01:04:18.705 align:middle line:90%


01:04:18.705 --> 01:04:20.080 align:middle line:84%
So at the level
of intuition, you

01:04:20.080 --> 01:04:22.770 align:middle line:84%
can think of this in terms
of degrees of freedom.

01:04:22.770 --> 01:04:25.360 align:middle line:90%


01:04:25.360 --> 01:04:29.500 align:middle line:84%
So the dimension of
this space tells us

01:04:29.500 --> 01:04:32.240 align:middle line:84%
how many degrees of freedom
we have to play with.

01:04:32.240 --> 01:04:34.430 align:middle line:84%
Each one of these
is a constraint.

01:04:34.430 --> 01:04:36.700 align:middle line:84%
And if the number of
degrees of freedom

01:04:36.700 --> 01:04:39.200 align:middle line:84%
is at least the
number of constraints,

01:04:39.200 --> 01:04:42.105 align:middle line:84%
then the theorem says we can
actually find a solution.

01:04:42.105 --> 01:04:45.910 align:middle line:90%


01:04:45.910 --> 01:04:48.520 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:04:48.520 --> 01:04:51.420 align:middle line:84%
The proof is essentially
the same as this.

01:04:51.420 --> 01:04:52.920 align:middle line:90%
So proof.

01:04:52.920 --> 01:04:55.380 align:middle line:90%
What do I need to check?

01:04:55.380 --> 01:04:56.470 align:middle line:90%
Well, fi.

01:04:56.470 --> 01:05:01.530 align:middle line:90%


01:05:01.530 --> 01:05:09.750 align:middle line:84%
So I just need to check
that fi are continuous

01:05:09.750 --> 01:05:14.735 align:middle line:84%
and fi of negative theta
is negative fi of theta.

01:05:14.735 --> 01:05:17.610 align:middle line:90%


01:05:17.610 --> 01:05:19.300 align:middle line:90%
So why is it continuous?

01:05:19.300 --> 01:05:22.740 align:middle line:84%
I won't do a full proof, but
if you adjust the coefficients

01:05:22.740 --> 01:05:25.110 align:middle line:84%
of this polynomial a
little bit, then the

01:05:25.110 --> 01:05:27.970 align:middle line:84%
set where it's positive
changes but only a little bit.

01:05:27.970 --> 01:05:30.490 align:middle line:84%
And so this volume should
only change a little bit.

01:05:30.490 --> 01:05:32.820 align:middle line:90%
That's continuity.

01:05:32.820 --> 01:05:34.660 align:middle line:90%
And why is it antipodal?

01:05:34.660 --> 01:05:39.450 align:middle line:84%
Well, if I switch
p to negative p--

01:05:39.450 --> 01:05:40.090 align:middle line:90%
actually, yeah.

01:05:40.090 --> 01:05:41.030 align:middle line:90%
Let me put p's here.

01:05:41.030 --> 01:05:46.680 align:middle line:90%


01:05:46.680 --> 01:05:49.070 align:middle line:84%
If I switch p to
negative p, then it

01:05:49.070 --> 01:05:51.260 align:middle line:90%
interchanges these two sets.

01:05:51.260 --> 01:05:57.410 align:middle line:84%
And so it switches
the sign of fi of p.

01:05:57.410 --> 01:05:59.780 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:05:59.780 --> 01:06:01.670 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

01:06:01.670 --> 01:06:02.610 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:06:02.610 --> 01:06:09.200 align:middle line:84%
And now f is going
to be f1 up to fn.

01:06:09.200 --> 01:06:11.960 align:middle line:84%
Now f is a map from
where to where?

01:06:11.960 --> 01:06:16.890 align:middle line:84%
f is a map from polynomials
of degree D on RN,

01:06:16.890 --> 01:06:21.125 align:middle line:90%
take away zero to RN.

01:06:21.125 --> 01:06:26.540 align:middle line:90%


01:06:26.540 --> 01:06:27.305 align:middle line:90%
Why is that?

01:06:27.305 --> 01:06:30.830 align:middle line:90%


01:06:30.830 --> 01:06:32.630 align:middle line:84%
I was waving my
hands a little bit

01:06:32.630 --> 01:06:37.100 align:middle line:84%
when I said that
fi is continuous

01:06:37.100 --> 01:06:43.400 align:middle line:84%
and fi is not
continuous at zero.

01:06:43.400 --> 01:06:47.390 align:middle line:84%
If the polynomial is zero, then
both of these sets are empty.

01:06:47.390 --> 01:06:51.460 align:middle line:84%
So I guess by the definition,
fi of 0 would be zero.

01:06:51.460 --> 01:06:57.650 align:middle line:84%
But then if I move p a
tiny bit so it's not zero,

01:06:57.650 --> 01:07:03.200 align:middle line:84%
then these sets will appear
and they take up most of space.

01:07:03.200 --> 01:07:07.120 align:middle line:84%
So there'll be a jump
discontinuity in those sets.

01:07:07.120 --> 01:07:08.890 align:middle line:84%
So the reason we
had to do this is

01:07:08.890 --> 01:07:12.580 align:middle line:84%
that fi is only continuous
on the space of polynomials

01:07:12.580 --> 01:07:13.790 align:middle line:90%
without zero.

01:07:13.790 --> 01:07:16.000 align:middle line:84%
So if I take a
non-zero polynomial

01:07:16.000 --> 01:07:18.072 align:middle line:84%
and I change the
coefficients a little bit,

01:07:18.072 --> 01:07:19.905 align:middle line:84%
then this set will only
change a little bit.

01:07:19.905 --> 01:07:26.075 align:middle line:90%


01:07:26.075 --> 01:07:26.575 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:07:26.575 --> 01:07:29.275 align:middle line:90%


01:07:29.275 --> 01:07:29.775 align:middle line:90%
Right.

01:07:29.775 --> 01:07:33.850 align:middle line:90%


01:07:33.850 --> 01:07:36.800 align:middle line:84%
So actually, I should say that
that's not completely trivial,

01:07:36.800 --> 01:07:38.450 align:middle line:90%
that fact.

01:07:38.450 --> 01:07:40.125 align:middle line:90%
It takes a little proving.

01:07:40.125 --> 01:07:47.130 align:middle line:90%


01:07:47.130 --> 01:07:51.190 align:middle line:84%
It's related to the fact that if
you have a non-zero polynomial,

01:07:51.190 --> 01:07:55.085 align:middle line:84%
then any of its level sets
cannot have positive volume.

01:07:55.085 --> 01:07:57.660 align:middle line:90%


01:07:57.660 --> 01:08:02.040 align:middle line:84%
If you have polynomial equals
3, that defines a hypersurface

01:08:02.040 --> 01:08:04.770 align:middle line:84%
and it cannot happen that
that hypersurface has positive

01:08:04.770 --> 01:08:05.785 align:middle line:90%
volume.

01:08:05.785 --> 01:08:07.410 align:middle line:84%
That's basically what
you need to check

01:08:07.410 --> 01:08:08.860 align:middle line:90%
that this is continuous.

01:08:08.860 --> 01:08:11.610 align:middle line:90%


01:08:11.610 --> 01:08:12.756 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:08:12.756 --> 01:08:15.100 align:middle line:84%
So this is a space
from here to here.

01:08:15.100 --> 01:08:22.050 align:middle line:84%
And to apply Borsuk-Ulam, I need
to have a sphere for my domain.

01:08:22.050 --> 01:08:24.779 align:middle line:84%
So this sphere is
sitting in here

01:08:24.779 --> 01:08:27.779 align:middle line:84%
as long as n is strictly
less than the dimension

01:08:27.779 --> 01:08:30.659 align:middle line:90%
of this space.

01:08:30.659 --> 01:08:32.576 align:middle line:84%
This is where we
use this hypothesis.

01:08:32.576 --> 01:08:39.779 align:middle line:90%


01:08:39.779 --> 01:08:40.519 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:08:40.519 --> 01:08:43.620 align:middle line:84%
And then Borsuk-Ulam
says that zero

01:08:43.620 --> 01:08:46.924 align:middle line:84%
is in the image of f, which
is what we're trying to prove.

01:08:46.924 --> 01:09:03.960 align:middle line:90%


01:09:03.960 --> 01:09:06.060 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:09:06.060 --> 01:09:08.130 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

01:09:08.130 --> 01:09:08.710 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:09:08.710 --> 01:09:10.835 align:middle line:84%
So we're getting close to
having a tool that we can

01:09:10.835 --> 01:09:12.960 align:middle line:90%
use to do this decomposition.

01:09:12.960 --> 01:09:17.170 align:middle line:84%
Now we have a little technical
issue or a little mismatch,

01:09:17.170 --> 01:09:21.420 align:middle line:84%
because what we want is
to start with a finite set

01:09:21.420 --> 01:09:23.850 align:middle line:84%
and have a cell decomposition
that kind of cuts it

01:09:23.850 --> 01:09:27.615 align:middle line:90%
into even pieces.

01:09:27.615 --> 01:09:29.920 align:middle line:84%
This proposition
is about open sets.

01:09:29.920 --> 01:09:32.640 align:middle line:84%
If we have a bunch of open
sets, we can simultaneously

01:09:32.640 --> 01:09:34.000 align:middle line:90%
cut them each in half.

01:09:34.000 --> 01:09:35.910 align:middle line:84%
So we need a version
where the open sets

01:09:35.910 --> 01:09:38.220 align:middle line:90%
are replaced by finite sets.

01:09:38.220 --> 01:09:39.399 align:middle line:90%
That's not difficult to do.

01:09:39.399 --> 01:09:42.107 align:middle line:90%
It's just a technical thing.

01:09:42.107 --> 01:09:42.940 align:middle line:90%
That's how it works.

01:09:42.940 --> 01:10:12.630 align:middle line:90%


01:10:12.630 --> 01:10:13.130 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:10:13.130 --> 01:10:16.400 align:middle line:90%
So proposition.

01:10:16.400 --> 01:10:22.110 align:middle line:84%
If Si contained in R2
or RN, I guess is OK,

01:10:22.110 --> 01:10:28.430 align:middle line:84%
our finite sets, i
equals 1 up to N,

01:10:28.430 --> 01:10:36.200 align:middle line:84%
and N is less than the
dimension of poly D of RN,

01:10:36.200 --> 01:10:41.350 align:middle line:84%
then there exists a non-zero
polynomial poly D of RN.

01:10:41.350 --> 01:10:46.420 align:middle line:90%


01:10:46.420 --> 01:10:48.100 align:middle line:90%
What does it mean?

01:10:48.100 --> 01:10:53.260 align:middle line:84%
So in some sense, we'd like this
polynomial to bisect these sets.

01:10:53.260 --> 01:10:56.080 align:middle line:84%
But we have to say
something slightly weaker,

01:10:56.080 --> 01:10:57.430 align:middle line:90%
and I'll explain why.

01:10:57.430 --> 01:11:03.610 align:middle line:84%
So that Si intersect p
positive is less than

01:11:03.610 --> 01:11:08.650 align:middle line:84%
or equal to Si over
2 and Si intersect

01:11:08.650 --> 01:11:13.130 align:middle line:84%
p negative is less
than Si over 2.

01:11:13.130 --> 01:11:16.723 align:middle line:90%


01:11:16.723 --> 01:11:17.630 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:11:17.630 --> 01:11:21.110 align:middle line:84%
So this set could be
a set of three points.

01:11:21.110 --> 01:11:24.580 align:middle line:84%
So it's not possible that
half of them will be positive

01:11:24.580 --> 01:11:26.150 align:middle line:84%
and half of them
will be negative.

01:11:26.150 --> 01:11:29.480 align:middle line:84%
So the best we could hope to
is that one would be positive,

01:11:29.480 --> 01:11:32.920 align:middle line:84%
one would be negative,
and one would be zero.

01:11:32.920 --> 01:11:35.370 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:11:35.370 --> 01:11:38.130 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:11:38.130 --> 01:11:38.710 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:11:38.710 --> 01:11:40.590 align:middle line:90%
So proof.

01:11:40.590 --> 01:11:42.780 align:middle line:84%
For any epsilon
bigger than zero,

01:11:42.780 --> 01:11:49.260 align:middle line:84%
let's say O epsilon i is the
epsilon neighborhood of Si.

01:11:49.260 --> 01:11:50.910 align:middle line:90%
So that's an open set.

01:11:50.910 --> 01:11:56.460 align:middle line:84%
And so we can apply
proposition to that set.

01:11:56.460 --> 01:12:04.570 align:middle line:84%
Apply polynomial ham
sandwich to O epsilon i.

01:12:04.570 --> 01:12:07.570 align:middle line:84%
And we output a
polynomial p epsilon,

01:12:07.570 --> 01:12:11.186 align:middle line:84%
which is in the unit sphere
in the space of polynomials.

01:12:11.186 --> 01:12:15.870 align:middle line:90%


01:12:15.870 --> 01:12:17.400 align:middle line:90%
And it bisects.

01:12:17.400 --> 01:12:24.810 align:middle line:84%
So we know that the
volume of O epsilon i

01:12:24.810 --> 01:12:28.860 align:middle line:84%
intersect p bigger
than zero is half

01:12:28.860 --> 01:12:31.540 align:middle line:90%
of the volume of O epsilon i.

01:12:31.540 --> 01:12:35.300 align:middle line:90%


01:12:35.300 --> 01:12:36.590 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:12:36.590 --> 01:12:38.370 align:middle line:84%
So we have this
for every epsilon.

01:12:38.370 --> 01:12:40.120 align:middle line:84%
And now we want to
take some kind of limit

01:12:40.120 --> 01:12:41.570 align:middle line:90%
as epsilon goes to zero.

01:12:41.570 --> 01:12:44.040 align:middle line:90%
And the sphere is compact.

01:12:44.040 --> 01:12:48.860 align:middle line:90%
So the sphere SN is compact.

01:12:48.860 --> 01:12:54.920 align:middle line:84%
So we have a
subsequence p epsilon.

01:12:54.920 --> 01:12:58.490 align:middle line:84%
Some subsequence of them
converges to a limit p,

01:12:58.490 --> 01:13:00.940 align:middle line:90%
which is a polynomial in SN.

01:13:00.940 --> 01:13:07.130 align:middle line:90%


01:13:07.130 --> 01:13:07.910 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:13:07.910 --> 01:13:10.825 align:middle line:84%
And the claim is that
the p does the job.

01:13:10.825 --> 01:13:13.990 align:middle line:90%


01:13:13.990 --> 01:13:19.160 align:middle line:84%
So let's say this is
the zero set of p.

01:13:19.160 --> 01:13:22.820 align:middle line:84%
Over here p is positive, and
down here, p is negative.

01:13:22.820 --> 01:13:28.640 align:middle line:84%
And suppose a particular Si was
not split up evenly like this.

01:13:28.640 --> 01:13:30.730 align:middle line:84%
So more than half of
that on that side.

01:13:30.730 --> 01:13:34.640 align:middle line:90%


01:13:34.640 --> 01:13:35.590 align:middle line:90%
Here, let me do that.

01:13:35.590 --> 01:13:38.550 align:middle line:90%


01:13:38.550 --> 01:13:39.050 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:13:39.050 --> 01:13:45.200 align:middle line:90%


01:13:45.200 --> 01:13:46.100 align:middle line:90%
There it is.

01:13:46.100 --> 01:13:48.060 align:middle line:90%
So why can't that happen?

01:13:48.060 --> 01:13:55.130 align:middle line:84%
Well, think about what p
epsilon would be doing.

01:13:55.130 --> 01:13:58.165 align:middle line:84%
So O epsilon i would
look like this.

01:13:58.165 --> 01:14:04.550 align:middle line:90%


01:14:04.550 --> 01:14:06.540 align:middle line:84%
And what would p
epsilon look like?

01:14:06.540 --> 01:14:10.640 align:middle line:84%
Well, it's a little
perturbation of p.

01:14:10.640 --> 01:14:13.490 align:middle line:90%
We have some convergence.

01:14:13.490 --> 01:14:17.000 align:middle line:84%
So that would be the
zero set of p epsilon.

01:14:17.000 --> 01:14:19.110 align:middle line:90%
Here is p epsilon is positive.

01:14:19.110 --> 01:14:22.160 align:middle line:90%
Here is p epsilon is negative.

01:14:22.160 --> 01:14:23.650 align:middle line:90%
And that violates this.

01:14:23.650 --> 01:14:30.720 align:middle line:90%


01:14:30.720 --> 01:14:31.220 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:14:31.220 --> 01:14:39.700 align:middle line:84%
So if Si intersect p is positive
is strictly greater than 1/2

01:14:39.700 --> 01:14:48.370 align:middle line:84%
of Si, then we have O epsilon
i intersect p epsilon positive

01:14:48.370 --> 01:14:53.890 align:middle line:84%
would be strictly greater
than 1/2 of O epsilon i

01:14:53.890 --> 01:14:55.184 align:middle line:90%
contradiction.

01:14:55.184 --> 01:15:00.755 align:middle line:90%


01:15:00.755 --> 01:15:01.255 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:15:01.255 --> 01:15:05.350 align:middle line:90%


01:15:05.350 --> 01:15:05.930 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:15:05.930 --> 01:15:08.385 align:middle line:84%
So now let's prove the
cell decomposition lemma.

01:15:08.385 --> 01:15:18.820 align:middle line:90%


01:15:18.820 --> 01:15:20.650 align:middle line:84%
So we prove the cell
decomposition lemma

01:15:20.650 --> 01:15:24.000 align:middle line:84%
by using the polynomial by using
this proposition many times.

01:15:24.000 --> 01:15:29.730 align:middle line:90%


01:15:29.730 --> 01:15:38.670 align:middle line:84%
So we have some set
of points X. And first

01:15:38.670 --> 01:15:46.420 align:middle line:84%
we use our proposition
with N equals 1.

01:15:46.420 --> 01:15:50.397 align:middle line:90%
And so D equals 1.

01:15:50.397 --> 01:15:52.480 align:middle line:84%
So we're actually an easy
case of our proposition.

01:15:52.480 --> 01:15:55.450 align:middle line:84%
We're only bisecting
this one set of points.

01:15:55.450 --> 01:15:59.460 align:middle line:90%
So here's p1 equals 0.

01:15:59.460 --> 01:16:05.100 align:middle line:84%
So the output is a polynomial
p1 of degree D1 equals 1.

01:16:05.100 --> 01:16:08.100 align:middle line:90%
And it bisects the set.

01:16:08.100 --> 01:16:15.150 align:middle line:84%
So we have X plus is the
set of X and X where p1 of X

01:16:15.150 --> 01:16:19.140 align:middle line:90%
is positive, et cetera.

01:16:19.140 --> 01:16:20.020 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:16:20.020 --> 01:16:23.910 align:middle line:84%
Then we use our proposition
with N equals 2,

01:16:23.910 --> 01:16:28.590 align:middle line:84%
and we get a polynomial
P2 of degree D2.

01:16:28.590 --> 01:16:31.880 align:middle line:84%
D2 would probably also
be 1, but let me just

01:16:31.880 --> 01:16:33.600 align:middle line:90%
put the general thing.

01:16:33.600 --> 01:16:39.170 align:middle line:84%
So it would be less
than our N2 to the 1/2.

01:16:39.170 --> 01:16:46.460 align:middle line:90%


01:16:46.460 --> 01:16:48.500 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:16:48.500 --> 01:16:54.410 align:middle line:90%
P2 bisects X plus and X minus.

01:16:54.410 --> 01:16:56.965 align:middle line:90%
So here's the zero set of P2.

01:16:56.965 --> 01:17:00.560 align:middle line:90%


01:17:00.560 --> 01:17:04.880 align:middle line:84%
And it bisects each half, so now
I've divided X into quarters.

01:17:04.880 --> 01:17:05.640 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:17:05.640 --> 01:17:07.370 align:middle line:90%
And we keep going.

01:17:07.370 --> 01:17:13.580 align:middle line:84%
So at step K I use my
proposition, and I have NK,

01:17:13.580 --> 01:17:19.100 align:middle line:84%
which is 2 to the K, and
DK, which is less than NK

01:17:19.100 --> 01:17:20.460 align:middle line:90%
to the 1/2.

01:17:20.460 --> 01:17:22.390 align:middle line:84%
So that's like 2
to the K over 2.

01:17:22.390 --> 01:17:26.150 align:middle line:90%


01:17:26.150 --> 01:17:31.300 align:middle line:84%
I'd output a polynomial
PK, and it bisects the 2

01:17:31.300 --> 01:17:33.235 align:middle line:90%
to the K minus 1 previous guys.

01:17:33.235 --> 01:17:34.770 align:middle line:90%
The 2 to the K previous guys.

01:17:34.770 --> 01:17:41.380 align:middle line:90%


01:17:41.380 --> 01:17:42.290 align:middle line:90%
I'll draw one more.

01:17:42.290 --> 01:17:45.010 align:middle line:84%
I have four pieces, and
I find a new polynomial

01:17:45.010 --> 01:17:46.310 align:middle line:90%
and I bisect all four.

01:17:46.310 --> 01:17:49.720 align:middle line:90%


01:17:49.720 --> 01:17:50.700 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:17:50.700 --> 01:17:53.260 align:middle line:90%
So now, when do I stop?

01:17:53.260 --> 01:18:01.180 align:middle line:84%
I choose the final K. So
2 to the K is S squared,

01:18:01.180 --> 01:18:05.950 align:middle line:84%
and that means the final
DK around 2 to the K over 2

01:18:05.950 --> 01:18:11.890 align:middle line:90%
is around S. OK.

01:18:11.890 --> 01:18:19.450 align:middle line:84%
So since I bisect
at every stage,

01:18:19.450 --> 01:18:24.070 align:middle line:84%
I get X intersect Oi
smaller than X over 2

01:18:24.070 --> 01:18:27.980 align:middle line:84%
to the K, which is
like X over S squared.

01:18:27.980 --> 01:18:29.235 align:middle line:90%
So that's my third bullet.

01:18:29.235 --> 01:18:34.600 align:middle line:90%


01:18:34.600 --> 01:18:39.520 align:middle line:84%
So I'm trying to prove
each cell has only a 1

01:18:39.520 --> 01:18:42.080 align:middle line:84%
over S squared fraction
of the original points.

01:18:42.080 --> 01:18:43.040 align:middle line:90%
We have that.

01:18:43.040 --> 01:18:47.740 align:middle line:84%
And then I'm trying to think
about how the lines intersect

01:18:47.740 --> 01:18:49.875 align:middle line:84%
the cells and how the
line intersects the walls.

01:18:49.875 --> 01:18:52.780 align:middle line:90%


01:18:52.780 --> 01:18:54.950 align:middle line:84%
So these are the
different cells.

01:18:54.950 --> 01:18:57.160 align:middle line:90%
And the red stuff is the walls.

01:18:57.160 --> 01:18:59.070 align:middle line:90%
So if I draw a line here.

01:18:59.070 --> 01:19:04.825 align:middle line:90%


01:19:04.825 --> 01:19:08.620 align:middle line:84%
The line intersected
with the wall

01:19:08.620 --> 01:19:15.280 align:middle line:84%
is smaller than D1 plus
dot, dot, dot plus DK,

01:19:15.280 --> 01:19:18.850 align:middle line:84%
because how many times
does a line intersect

01:19:18.850 --> 01:19:22.140 align:middle line:90%
the zero set of a polynomial.

01:19:22.140 --> 01:19:23.450 align:middle line:90%
It's at most the degree.

01:19:23.450 --> 01:19:26.490 align:middle line:90%


01:19:26.490 --> 01:19:28.098 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:19:28.098 --> 01:19:33.030 align:middle line:84%
So these degrees are
bounded by 2 to the k.

01:19:33.030 --> 01:19:33.910 align:middle line:90%
Over 2.

01:19:33.910 --> 01:19:37.530 align:middle line:90%
So this is a geometric series.

01:19:37.530 --> 01:19:40.770 align:middle line:84%
It's bounded by its last
term 2 to the K over 2,

01:19:40.770 --> 01:19:45.215 align:middle line:84%
which is around S. So
that's the second bullet.

01:19:45.215 --> 01:19:47.820 align:middle line:90%


01:19:47.820 --> 01:19:51.430 align:middle line:84%
And every time this line moves
from one cell to another,

01:19:51.430 --> 01:19:52.660 align:middle line:90%
it has to cross the wall.

01:19:52.660 --> 01:19:54.690 align:middle line:84%
So that also bounds
the number of cells

01:19:54.690 --> 01:19:56.166 align:middle line:90%
that the line intersects.

01:19:56.166 --> 01:20:02.760 align:middle line:90%


01:20:02.760 --> 01:20:07.140 align:middle line:84%
So that ends the proof or proof
sketch of the cell decomposition

01:20:07.140 --> 01:20:09.030 align:middle line:90%
lemma.

01:20:09.030 --> 01:20:11.600 align:middle line:90%
Any questions or comments?

01:20:11.600 --> 01:20:20.000 align:middle line:90%